<FIRST>r a AM-IdahoFires 1stLd-Writethru a0763 07-29 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Idaho Fires, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0763,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Guard Joins Fight Against Forest Fires</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT that governor authorized use of, sted sent
in, military reinforcements; SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that 3,000, sted
15,000, people are involved in fighting 15,000 acres of fires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Cecil Andrus declared a state of
extreme emergency Friday, putting military reinforcements on call
to help the battle against hundreds of forest fires burning out of
control.
   The emergency proclamation, which allows the state to use the
National Guard, will last for 30 days or until the fire danger
subsides. The Boise Interagency Fire Center estimated about 3,000
people were working as firefighters or support personnel to battle
15,000 acres of Idaho fires.
   The weather cooperated in northern Idaho with high humidity that
slowed the flames, while the opposite was true for the Boise
National Forest.
   ``The humidity dropped considerably,'' said Lynette Davis, Boise
forest spokeswoman. ``When the air dried out, the fires got up and
ran.''
   A lightning storm earlier this week covered central Idaho with
500 fires, some limited to just a burning tree. Firefighters
concentrated on the larger blazes, while parachuting smokejumpers
or helicopter-borne crews tackled the small ones.
   The containment of small fires and shuffling of crews Friday
left it difficult to assess total acreage burned or manpower on the
fire lines.
   The top-priority fire in the state was the 1,500-acre Fleming
Creek blaze near Banks, north of Boise, said Pam Gardner, fire
information officer for the Payette forest north of Boise. It
burned on state and Boise forest land.
   The second fire of concern was the 600-acre Dollar Creek fire
near the South Fork of the Salmon River east of Cascade because of
the chance its destruction of ground cover could lead to erosion
into the river.
   Fire bosses in the Boise Bureau of Land Management District
focused on the 6,500-acre Deer Creek blaze near Mann Creek north of
Weiser, which had tripled in size since Thursday and was burning in
critical sharptail grouse habitat.
   In the Payette National Forest, about 500 firefighters from all
over the West had contained 70 of 130 fires and the Federal
Aviation Administration erected a temporary tower at the McCall
airport to monitor the scores of retardant bombers and smoke jumper
planes in the region.
</TEXT>
