<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchKilling     07-29 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Killing,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted in Killing of Church Volunteer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was found guilty of first-degree murder
Friday in the killing of a church volunteer, more than two years
after he was captured in the longest manhunt in Missouri history.
   The jury deliberated for 2{ hours before returning the verdict
against John David Brown, 35, in Phelps County Circuit Court.
   The penalty phase of the two-week trial is scheduled to begin at
9:30 a.m. Saturday, and the state is asking for the death penalty.
The jury can recommend either death or life imprisonment.
   Tim Finnical, an assistant attorney general and the lead
prosecutor in the case, said testimony from ballistics experts
showed the gun Brown had when he was arrested in Ada, Okla., was
the one that killed caretaker Claude Long in a Doolittle church on
April 1, 1987.
   ``Circumstantial evidence conclusively _ conclusively _ proves
John David Brown murdered this man,'' Finnical told the jury.
   Brown's attorney, Brad Kessler, had questioned the validity of
the ballistics results. ``What you have here is the state grasping
at straws. They have to put someone in the church,'' Kessler said.
   At the time Long was killed, Brown was the subject of a massive
manhunt after a man matching his description fled from a Rolla
motel room a few days earlier. A police officer was wounded in that
incident.
</TEXT>
