<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BroadcastDeregulation     07-29 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Broadcast Deregulation,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC `Voodoo Priests' Not Helping Radio</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 2 p.m. EDT. Time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio is being ill-served by ``voodoo
priests'' at the Federal Communications Commission who seem to
think just about anyone should be able to own a station, a
broadcasting lobbyist says.
   A deregulation-minded FCC has been kind to broadcasters in many
ways during the 1980s, but has sometimes gone too far in its rush
to impose a free-market ethic, said Edward O. Fritts, president of
the National Association of Broadcasters.
   ``If there were a modern-day Rip Van Winkle broadcaster who had
gone to sleep in 1980 and reawakened this year, he would scarcely
believe the changes,'' Fritts said in remarks prepared for delivery
today at the Idaho State Association of Broadcasters meeting in Sun
Valley.
   ``The entire communications landscape has changed,'' he said.
``Deregulation has come faster and gone farther than our industry
ever asked or dreamed of.''
   Under FCC Chairman Mark S. Fowler and his predecessor, Dennis R.
Patrick, the Fairness Doctrine has been lifted and broadcasters
received favorable improvements in the license-renewal process.
   Fritts said broadcasters were grateful for those victories, but
that the FCC has caused other headaches.
   Noting that the FCC loosened rules for acquiring radio station
licenses, Fritts said it appeared the commission had ``become so
obsessed with regulation by marketplace economic theory that it
seemingly is interested in providing every man, woman and child
with their own radio station.''
   ``Ole Rip would be surprised that the FCC has no apparent
concern for preserving the system of local service by financially
healthy stations that has served the American public so well for
the past 70 years,'' he said. ``Our awakening broadcaster would
think his world was being ruled by voodoo priests.
   ``As a result of the FCC's Alice-in-Wonderland allocations
policies, it is faced with a growing backlog of applications for
new facilities and minor station modifications.
   Fritts said an FCC official acknowledged recently that a new
ruling allowing increased power for small FM stations may increase
the application backlog from six months to 18 months.
   And it was particularly galling to broadcasters, he said, that
even as the backlog grows, a deficit-conscious Congress wants to
increase application fees by 13 percent.
   Fritts lashed out at FCC proposals to hold lotteries, auctions
and private negotiations to allocate and assign station licenses.
   ``How can the commission say with a straight face that is can
choose broadcast applicants who will best serve the public interest
by reading ping-pong balls or conducting lotteries?''
   The FCC, Fritts said, ``has allowed so many new stations on the
AM band that it has created destructive interference and undermined
the financial health of many stations to the determinant of local
service.''
</TEXT>
