<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DroughtDisaster     07-29 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought Disaster,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dole Offers Compromise All-Crops Disaster Relief Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a week of partisan bickering, farm-state
senators are inching toward compromise on legislation to provide
federal payments to producers suffering crop losses from drought
and other weather-related damage.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas dropped his
opposition Friday to an across-the-board disaster relief package
and offered a proposal that a Democratic leader said could clear
the way for a bipartisan agreement.
   ``Sen. Dole's flexibility will lead to an agreement on a final
package that treats all farmers fairly,'' Sen. Patrick Leahy,
D-Vt., chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee, said in a
statement.
   ``We are moving toward common ground that fairly covers all
demonstrated crop losses within reasonable spending levels.''
   Dole had been leading opposition to a Democratic-sponsored
measure providing $955 million to cover weather-related crop losses.
   Dole's proposal, estimated to cost $891 million, would provide
more assistance to farmers of the major grains who bought federal
crop insurance and less to the hundreds of other commodities _ the
so-called non-program crops _ because they are not covered by
federal subsidy and price support programs.
   The Bush administration has said about $870 million in
agricultural budget savings could be used for farm disaster relief.
   So far, the dispute in the Senate has been over what crops
should qualify for federal payments. But pressure is building on
lawmakers to take action.
   Congress is scheduled to recess Aug. 5 for a month-long
vacation, and most farm-state members don't want to return home
without having sent an aid bill to the White House.
   Dole has complained that the Democratic measure, approved by the
Agriculture Committee on a party-line vote earlier in the week, was
potentially too expensive because it covered more than 500 crops.
But he moved closer to the Democratic package Friday with his
compromise proposal.
   Faring best under Dole's proposal would be producers of wheat,
cotton, rice, corn and other crops participating in federal
commodity programs and those who bought federal crop insurance.
They would be eligible for assistance on losses above 35 percent,
with payments covering 65 percent of their lost income.
   Farmers without crop insurance, but enrolled in the federal farm
programs, would have to suffer losses of at least 40 percent, under
Dole's plan. Peanuts, tobacco and sugar beet growers would be
covered by the same provision.
   Soybean and sunflower farmers would be eligible for assistance
if they suffered losses above 45 percent.
   Most crops not covered by government commodity programs,
everything from peaches and cherries to dry edible beans and
potatoes, must suffer losses exceeding 50 percent and would then
receive payments covering 50 percent of the producer's lost income.
   The same 50-50 formula would apply to farmers who are not
enrolled in federal commodity programs but grow wheat, corn, grain
sorghum and other so-called program crops.
   Under the Democratic package, farmers with crops enrolled in
government commodity programs would qualify for assistance if they
suffered 40 percent losses. Farmers of other crops would have to
show a 45 percent loss. The measure provided 65 percent payments
for both.
   A $1 billion disaster relief bill passed by the House last month
would require a minimum loss of 35 percent for any crop to receive
assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
