<FIRST>r w PM-US-Soviet     07-29 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Marshal Says USSR Can Keep Pace With Stealth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top military adviser to Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev says the B-2 stealth bomber won't give the United
States an edge over the Soviets.
   ``For every action in life there is a reaction,'' Soviet Marshal
Sergei Akhromeyev told the National Press Club on Friday.
   ``So if the creation, development and deployment of the B-2 is
an action, in one way or another there will be some sort of
reaction from the Soviet Union.''
   The House this week voted to suspend production of the B-2 until
the Pentagon scales back the high-priced program, and said the
administration must show the stealth can successfully evade radar
detection and penetrate Soviet airspace before production resumes.
   Bush and his defense officials have lobbied hard for the bomber
as a highly advanced piece of technology that would outstrip Soviet
radar capabilities.
   Akhromeyev's speech and question-and-answer session was the
first by a senior Soviet official at the Press Club since Premier
Nikita Krushchev in 1959.
   Akhromeyev told an audience that included Adm. William J. Crowe,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, that the trip in which he
gave historic testimony to Congress had encouraged him that Soviet
relations with the United States will continue to improve.
   Still, he said that while the decrease in tension between NATO
and Warsaw Pact countries was ``a tremendous accomplishment ... the
military threat, unfortunately, is still there.''
   Akhromeyev, wearing his Red Army uniform with 11 rows of
ribbons, went from the Press Club to a private White House meeting
with President Bush, Vice President Dan Quayle, Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney and Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
</TEXT>
