<FIRST>r i PM-BatBan     07-29 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bat Ban,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holy Censorship! Film Board Bans Children Under 12 From Seeing Batman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Batman'' is winging its way to Britain, but
youngsters under 12 will have to stick to comic books to catch the
Caped Crusader. The national film board says the popular movie is
unsuitable for little kids.
   The British Board of Film Classification applied its new ``12''
category to the movie that opens Aug. 11 in Britain, with Michael
Keaton playing the title role and Jack Nicholson starring as his
evil nemesis, the Joker.
   The category bars youngsters under 12 from a film no matter what
parents decide. In the United States, the comparable PG-13 is only
an advisory guideline for parents, while the R rating restricts
minors from seeing a particular movie.
   A spokesman for filmmaker Warner Brothers said the British
decision was ``quite in keeping with the nature of the film. It is
for the producers to decide what kind of film they wish to make and
what they have come up with is not like the old comic strip
television series from the '60s. This Batman comes out at night.''
   A film board spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity in
keeping with British practice, said the new designation was created
because the old ``15'' classification wound up keeping children
between the ages of 12 and 14 out of movies that may be suitable
for them.
   Early Times, a children's newspaper, said: ``We are concerned
that many children under 12, in the light of the hype and publicity
over Batman, will be bitterly disappointed over the rating of this
film as 12 Certificate particularly as the impression has been
created that it is a summer family film.''
</TEXT>
