<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Kidnapping Bjt   07-29 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Kidnapping, Bjt,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abduction of Shiite Leader Could Lead to Release of Hostages, Israel
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The kidnapping of a Shiite Moslem cleric by
Israeli commandos could put pressure on pro-Iranian terrorists to
free some of the foreign hostages held in Lebanon, according to
Israeli officials.
   ``Clearly when you capture one of their top leaders it can deter
terrorism and you have a certain amount of leverage in your
hands,'' Army spokesman Col. Raanan Gissin said of Friday's raid by
helicopter-borne commandos.
   Seized by the commandos were cleric Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, his
cousin Ahmed Obeid and a friend, Majid Fahs, a Lebanese police
spokesman told reporters.
   Gissin said Obeid and two ``assistants'' were ``safely in
Israeli hands and undergoing questioning.''
   One person was killed in the assault on an apartment building in
the village of Jibchit, 20 miles north of the Israeli border and 35
miles south of Beirut, according to Lebanese and Israeli reports.
   Lebanese police said a neighbor, Hussein Abu Zeid, opened the
door of his apartment during the raid and was shot to death by the
commandos. Israel radio said Zeid was one of Obeid's bodyguards.
   Even before Friday's abductions, some Israeli officials said the
capture of a Lebanese Shiite leader supported by Iran could
influence the release of three Israeli servicemen kidnapped in
southern Lebanon in 1986.
   Lebanese security sources suggested Obeid may have been abducted
in a plan to exchange him for U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R.
Higgins or other foreign hostages. The sources also have linked
Obeid with Higgins' abduction.
   Higgins, of Danville, Ky., was kidnapped in southern Lebanon
Feb. 17, 1988, while serving with an observer group attached to the
U.N. peacekeeping force in southern Lebanon.
   Seventeen foreign hostages are held in Lebanon, including nine
Americans and three Britons but not counting the Israeli
servicemen. It is belived most of the hostages are captives of
pro-Iranian terrorist groups affiliated with Hezbollah, or Party of
God.
   Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, has been held the longest. He was kidnapped March
16, 1985, and a Shiite Moslem group, Islamic Holy War, has said it
is holding him.
   Gissin called Obeid the ``equivalent of the commander of the
(Hezbollah) terrorist organization in South Lebanon.''
   Obeid, 33, has denied involvment with the fundamenalist Islamic
group but Israel and the U.S. State Department have called him a
member of Hezbollah.
   Britain's Foreign Office deplored the kidnapping, saying it
could jeopardize the lives of the foreign hostages and called for
his release.
   Gissin disagreed and said Hezbollah leaders will ``now think
twice before harming their hostages.''
   ``They value the lives of their leaders far more then they value
the lives of their suicide fighters,'' he added.
   Gissen said Hezbollah guerrillas have attempted at least 20
cross-border raids into Israel this year.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman told reporters, ``Israel
said many times in the past that when the fight against terrorism
is at stake, it reserves the right to respond whenever it finds it
suitable and effective.''
   The three Israeli troopers believed held hostage in Lebanon are
soldiers Rahamim Alsheikh and Yossi Fink, captured Feb. 17, 1986,
when guerrillas ambushed their patrol, and air force navigator Ron
Arad seized Oct. 16, 1986, when his plane was shot down.
   Lebanese police, the Israeli news media and witnesses gave these
accounts of the Jibchit raid:
   Three helicopters took part in the operation. About 12 commandos
with silencer-equipped pistols surrounded Obeid's building and
forced their way into his apartment.
   Israeli television said the troopers blasted the front door of
Obeid's apartment with plastic explosives, seized Obeid and the
other men and rushed them to a helicopter that departed in the
attack that lasted less then 30 minutes.
   Obeid's wife, Mona, was locked in a room with her hands tied and
her mouth taped shut.
   Iran's Foreign Ministry issued a statment saying, ``This
shameless act by the Zionist regime will not remain unanswered by
the Moslem and combatant forces.''
</TEXT>
