<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. John Y. Brown Jr. no longer
eats fried chicken, which made him a millionaire.
   At 55, with his heart mending, he said he intends to eat less,
exercise more, condense his business interests and devote more time
to his family.
   Coronary heart disease led him to quadruple bypass surgery this
month.
   ``I feel like I've gotten a second chance. I'm really very
happy, very optimistic,'' he said in a recent interview. ``I
realized one thing. You can't cheat the system.''
   For many years, Brown worked hard and played hard. He drank,
smoked, traveled and gambled.
   Brown said he has started walking for exercise and is often
accompanied by his wife, Phyllis George Brown, the former Miss
America and TV anchorwoman.
   Brown sold Kentucky Fried Chicken in 1971 but still has several
restaurant ventures going.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former first lady Nancy Reagan launched the
latest phase of her anti-drug crusade with a visit to a drug
rehabilitation center.
   After meeting with female clients and their children at the Via
Avanta drug center, Mrs. Reagan said her foundation would
distribute grants to similar centers in the Los Angeles area,
although Via Avanta won't be considered for a grant this year.
   The grants will begin small and grow according to contributions,
Mrs. Reagan said Thursday.
   The live-in center is one of a handful in California that caters
to women who have children or are pregnant.
   ``I've never seen this kind of a program before ... they tell me
there are a couple of others,'' Mrs. Reagan said. ``I think it's
very important, especially for young mothers.''
   Meanwhile, former President Reagan, accompanied by Secret
Service agents and publisher Malcolm Forbes, visited the all-male
Bohemian Club in Santa Rosa.
   Reagan has been a member for years at the exclusive club, a
2,700-acre grove near the community of Monte Rio about 15 miles
west of Santa Rosa.
   Reagan arrived Friday. It was not known how long he planned to
stay.
