<FIRST>u a AM-RootSued 2ndLd-Writethru a0768 07-29 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Root Sued, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0768,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Orleans Group Claims Root Represented It Improperly Before FCC</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Root is...', with two grafs to UPDATE with Root
at parent's Ohio home and no comment from his father. Picks up 6th graf,
`Root had...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Root, the lawyer who survived a
mysterious gunshot and a plane crash near the Bahamas, has been
sued by investors who claim he cost them $125,000 in a case before
the Federal Communications Commission.
   The suit was filed Thursday in federal court by a group of
investors who tried to get an FCC license in 1987 to build an FM
radio station.
   Root specialized in that type of litigation. But the lawsuit
claims he committed legal malpractice by lying about some things,
failing to attend to details associated with getting a license, and
keeping the investors from getting a cash settlement from another
group that ultimately got the license.
   Belle Chasse Radio Limited Partnership, the group represented by
Root, and five other groups were trying to get the same license
approval for the New Orleans area, according to the suit.
   Root, of Alexandria, Va., is recovering from the bullet wound
and other injuries stemming from the crash of a small plane he was
piloting July 13. He is at his parent's home in Plymouth, Ohio,
about 50 miles southwest of Cleveland.
   His father, Thomas F. Root, contacted by telephone early
Saturday about the suit, said, ``I'm not aware of it, and I
wouldn't have any comment.'' The elder Root said his son was not
available for comment.
   Root had set out on a business trip, flying from Arlington, Va.,
to Rocky Mount, N.C., and later told air traffic controllers he was
having trouble breathing. He put his plane on autopilot and
military planes kept watch on him until his plane ran out of fuel
and ditched near the Bahamas.
   Root says he was unconscious until his plane hit the water, but
the military pilots said they saw his head move. He also insists he
does not know how he received the gunshot wound to the abdomen,
which was found after his rescue.
   The lawsuit claims that Root told his group's lead investor, C.
Lee Armstrong Clear, that the other competing groups would be
willing to pay Belle Chasse a $125,000 settlement for dropping its
license application.
   However, the suit alleges, Root subsequently told attorneys for
the other groups that he had been having trouble locating his
clients, and that Clear and Belle Chasse had decided to dismiss
their application.
   The FCC filed an order of involuntary dismissal against the
application and Root allowed it to go through without telling the
Belle Chasse investors what he had done, the suit alleged.
   Attorney Bruce Waltzer said the group that eventually won the
license paid settlements to all of the other groups except Belle
Chasse.
   FCC officials said last week that Root, who was paid about
$50,000 by the Belle Chasse group, had been involved in many cases
in which groups received settlements in exchange for dropping their
applications.
</TEXT>
