<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Typhoon     07-29 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Typhoon,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Kills 11; Thousands Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Judy was downgraded to a
tropical depression today after it had slammed into South Korea,
leaving 11 people dead and thousands homeless from widespread
flooding.
   The National Disaster Center said all the victims died in
landslides or cave-ins in the southern port city of Pusan and
surrounding areas, which were hardest hit.
   The media quoted higher casualty tolls from the typhoon. KBS
state television reported 19 people killed or missing. Two fishing
boats sank in rough seas and 10,000 acres of paddy fields were
flooded, it said.
   The weather bureau downgraded Typhoon Judy to a tropical
depression about dawn today and said it had lost its force and been
replaced by an ordinary low pressure system with heavy rains.
   Typhoon Judy packed winds of up to 78 miles an hour as it hit
the coast Friday, dumping up to 11.7 inches of rain in already
flood-stricken southern areas.
   One elderly woman was killed when a wall of her home collapsed,
and a fisherman was swept into the sea, news reports said.
   Survivors were wading through knee-deep water to salvage their
belongings, the reports said.
   Typhoon Judy left 40,000 people homeless and the toll of dead
and displaced is expected to rise as communications with remote
areas are restored, the Disaster Center said.
   Judy is the third typhoon in two weeks in Asia, where storms and
flooding have killed at least 2,500 people and left hundreds of
thousands homeless since mid-June.
   The typhoon swept across Japan earlier Friday, killing three and
leaving hundreds of thousands without electricity before heading
for the Korean peninsula.
   In South Korea, it followed five days of torrential seasonal
rains that already had left thousands homeless and dozens dead in
southern areas. The combined toll from floods and rains this week
was 85 killed and 47 missing, said the Disaster Center. Nationwide,
about 112,000 people were homeless, it said.
   It estimated property damage at more than $231 million.
   The U.S. Air Force based in Osan, 25 miles south of Seoul, used
helicopters and 20 paramedics to rescue stranded flood victims.
   A U.S. military spokesman said they picked up 77 flood victims
Friday, using rubber boats to reach some stricken areas.
</TEXT>
