<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StokesTrial     07-29 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stokes Trial,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Mayor Stokes Cleared In Petty Theft Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHAKER HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury cleared former Cleveland
Mayor Carl B. Stokes of charges he shoplifted a $17.25 bag of dog
food from a pet store.
   The eight-member jury deliberated on the petty theft charge for
2{ hours before returning the verdict Friday night in the suburban
Shaker Heights court.
   The dismissal was received graciously by prosecutor K.J.
Montgomery. Stokes is a municipal judge in Cleveland.
   ``The jury has done their job,'' Montgomery said. ``I just hope
the judge doesn't have any problems from this incident.''
   Stokes was mayor from 1967 to 1971 and then worked as a news
reporter for WNBC-TV in New York. He returned to Cleveland in 1980
to become a labor lawyer and was elected to the municipal bench in
1983.
   Stokes, 62, testified that he twice entered the Pad &amp; Fin pet
store June 2 through a rear door and asked two dog groomers about
buying dog food for his rottweiler Max. Each time the groomers said
the store's regular employees had not yet arrived for the day,
Stokes said Friday.
   ``I said, `The hell with it, I'll get a bag of dog food and come
back and pay for it in the afternoon,''' he said.
   Stokes said he was in a hurry to drive to downtown Cleveland for
three morning appointments.
   He returned to the store five hours later intending to pay for
the dog food, he said, but sensed hostility from two regular
employees he had known from past trips to the store, and again left
without paying, afraid that even the appearance of wrongdoing could
ruin his career.
   Last December, a hardware store security guard stopped Stokes
with a $2.39 screwdriver in his pocket. Stokes said he had
forgotten to pay for it. The store did not pursue shoplifting
charges.
   Three of Stokes' children and his brother, Democratic Rep. Louis
Stokes, were present for the verdict.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
