<SECOND>PM-Fire Rescue,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Rescues Family, Grandchildren From Burning House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOTHAN, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman rescued her husband, daughter, and
six grandchildren from her burning home, then broke a window to
save a seventh who had not awakened, officials said.
   Dorothy Goodman, 55, said she saw a bright light when she went
into her kitchen early Friday to get something to drink.
   ``I saw the whole couch in the den was on fire,'' she said.
   She said ran to the bedrooms, where she awakened her husband,
Floyd, and her daughter, Lora, 22. She then roused her six
grandsons, ages 4 to 10.
   ``I shook them and dragged them out of the bed,'' Mrs. Goodman
said.
   Once outside, Mrs. Goodman realized a child was missing. She
went back into the house, but the heat of the fire forced her out.
She knocked out a bedroom window where 6-year-old April Griffin was
sleeping.
   Deputy Fire Chief Gerald McDaniel said Mrs. Goodman cut her arms
when she broke the window to reach her granddaughter.
   He said a cigarette dropped into the couch probably ignited the
fire.
