<FIRST>r a PM-InmatePetition     07-29 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inmate Petition,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Want to Fix Up Old Prison Themselves, Keep It Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates at a state prison want a federal
judge to let them fix up the 91-year-old building themselves and
use it for treatment and training programs.
   The Tennessee State Prison was ordered closed by U.S. District
Judge Thomas Higgins as a result of a lawsuit filed on behalf of
all prisoners in the state. The 1982 order declared the state's
prison system unconstitutional because of overcrowding and poor
conditions.
   ``We're not asking for justice,'' prisoner James B. Proctor told
Gov. Ned McWherter during a recent meeting on the renovation
proposal. ``We're asking for mercy.''
   Of the prison's 1,200 inmates, 506 signed a petition filed
Friday with Higgins to keep the prison open for vocational and
educational programs and psychiatric, drug and alcohol treatment
for long-term prisoners.
   The prisoners propose that the prison house 500 convicts who
have served at least eight years on sentences of 35 years or more.
   The court orders require the prison to close as soon as enough
new prisons open to provide room for its inmates. One prison is to
open in September, another in January and three more by 1992.
   A month ago, Higgins denied the state's petition to renovate
part of the Tennesee State prison as a special facility for 500 sex
offenders and mentally and physically disabled inmates.
   But the petitioning inmates said they hope to change Higgins'
mind.
   ``By using an inmate workforce, labor, construction and
renovation costs will be drastically reduced,'' they said in court
papers. ``By bringing education, vocational training and industry
into such an environment, an inmate can contribute to his own
support.''
   Higgins has said any modification in previous orders must first
be approved by Patrick McManus, a special prison master he
appointed to keep tabs on the state's progress in upgrading the
prison system.
   Higgins said in his order last month that he supports the
position of Gordon Bonnyman, a lawyer who has represented prisoners
since 1975. Bonnyman also wants Tennessee State Prison closed.
   Bonnyman said Friday he would have no comment on the prisoners'
request.
</TEXT>
