<FIRST>r a PM-SovietHelp     07-29 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Help,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Spy Ship Turns Fleeing Cubans Over to US</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Cubans who survived almost a week at sea were
rescued by a Soviet spy ship prowling off Cape Canaveral, which
turned them over to the Coast Guard.
   U.S. officials, who had no recollection of any previous rescue
by Soviet sailors of fleeing Cubans, were puzzling over why the
ship had not turned over the men, found floating 26 miles off the
Florida coast, to Cuban authorities.
   ``In the time I've been here in Miami, this is the first time,''
Coast Guard spokesman Luis Diaz said Friday. ``I've had two tours
of duty here, so this is something new for us.''
   The men were badly sunburned, dehydrated and exhausted after a
six-day, 125-mile voyage during which they lost a companion and at
one point resorted to catching a bird with bare hands and eating it
raw.
   They were taken to Jackson Memorial Hospital and treated for
dehydration and severe sunburn. A hospital spokesman said they were
in stable condition Friday night.
   The Soviet ship, identified in the reference book Jane's
Fighting Ships as the 274-foot Zaporozhye, spotted the three
clinging to an inner tube and rescued them Friday morning, the
Coast Guard said. The Soviet captain refused to allow a Coast Guard
party to board, and the Cubans were transferred by raft to a patrol
boat for their trip to Miami.
   The refugees identified themselves as Arsenio Gomez Hernandez,
46, his son Pedro Gomez Cruz, 17, and Arsenio's brother Humberto
Valentin Gomez, 48.
   Junior Arlais Gomez, 20, cousin and nephew to the others, was
lost at sea.
   The men had secretly built a 12-foot wooden rowboat in Cuba,
which they loaded with supplies and tied to a tractor-trailer tire
inner tube.
   The rowboat overturned Monday night in rough seas, spilling
their provisions. The men clung to the inner tube.
   They caught some small fish by hand, Arsenio Gomez said. A
seabird landed on his head at one point, he said. He managed to
catch it and they ate it.
   The men lost track of time and weren't sure when Arlais became
delirious and thought he saw the lights of Miami. He let go of the
tube and drifted away, they said.
   Cuban refugees who make it to Florida usually are turned over to
the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service and released to
relatives after questioning.
   The Coast Guard has picked up 97 Cubans on rafts this year, 31
this month alone.
   The Soviet ship has been operating for several months off Cape
Canaveral on intelligence-collecting operations, said U.S. Navy Lt.
Cmdr. Steve Burnett, Atlantic fleet spokesman in Norfolk, Va.
   Coast Guardsman Jeff Slater said the Soviets may not have
realized the men were fleeing Cuba. ``The first information we
tried to get was their nationality,'' he said. ``The Soviets
answered `either Cuban or Haitian.' ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
