<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Attendants     07-29 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Attendants,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight 232 Attendants Describe Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donna McGrady says she prayed along with fellow
flight attendants as United Flight 232 headed for a fiery crash
near an Iowa cornfield, then gave thanks as survivors emerged from
the wreckage.
   ``We all prayed _ we had our various moments of prayer,'' Ms.
McGrady recalled Friday.
   Ms. McGrady broke down in tears Friday at a news conference
where five United Airlines flight attendants who survived the crash
joined three others who helped on the ground. The news conference,
at O'Hare International Airport, was sponsored by their union, the
Association of Flight Attendants.
   Seven of the eight working attendants aboard the DC-10 were
among the 185 survivors. Flight attendant Rene LeBeau, 23, of
Schaumburg, was one of the 111 who died in the July 19 crash near
Sioux City, Iowa. The three-man cockpit crew survived, as well as a
non-working pilot who helped out.
   When the tail section where she was seated came to rest, Ms.
McGrady said she and another flight attendant helped people out of
the wreckage and then realized the severity of the crash.
   ``At that particular time, to come out and to look and to see
nothing but debris ... ' ' she said, her voice breaking.
   ``I said, `Oh, God, where is the other part of the aircraft?'''
   But the sorrow was tempered by joy at seeing so many survivors,
Ms. McGrady said.
   ``I said, `Thank you, Jesus, for the things that you've done for
us because we know there's no other way we could have made it
without your presence,''' she said.
   ``It was so good to see them,'' said flight attendant Becky
Larson, who were not aboard the plane but had helped survivors at
the crash scene.
   ``We just hugged them and loved them and kissed them and we were
so happy to see them,'' Ms. Larson said.
   Many of the dozens of United employees who attended dabbed at
tears during the news conference.
   Janice Brown, head flight attendant on the ill-fated DC-10, said
she cannot think of anything the flight attendants could have done
to save more people, and could not explain how some survived while
others did not.
   ``I'm not going to second-guess God,'' Ms. Brown said.
   Flight attendant Timothy Owens of Baltimore, who was seated in
the middle of the plane, said ``the tail section of the plane just
split apart and I saw a big beam of sunlight just coming through
the big opening in the back.''
   The flight attendants did not know at first that Ms. LeBeau had
been killed, Ms. McGrady said.
   After the news conference, Chicago-based United held a private
memorial service in the same room for Ms. LeBeau and four
non-working United employees who died in the crash. An airline
spokesman said more than 380 people attended.
   One flight attendant who was part of the plane's crew and a
non-working attendant who assisted during the crash were still
hospitalized Friday.
   The hospitalized flight attendant, Barbara Gillaspie, said
Friday from the Missouri hospital where she is being treated for
fractured vertebrae that she wants to fly again. Mrs. Gillaspie
said she will wait for physicians to say when she can return to the
skies.
   ``When I get the first OK, I'm going,'' she said.
</TEXT>
