<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Iraq     07-29 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Iraq,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Blocks Negotiations To Sell Jets To Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ministry of Defense has stopped British
Aerospace from negotiating a $500-million deal to sell Hawk trainer
jets to Iraq, officials said.
   Britain's domestic Press Association quoted unnamed government
sources as saying British Aerospace had hoped to sell 500 of the
jets to Iraq.
   A British Aerospace spokesman said Friday he could not comment
on the price of any possible deal, saying ``it wasn't a foregone
conclusion we had an order.
   ``The MOD (Ministry of Defense) vetoed us negotiating,'' he said.
   A ministry spokeswoman said the government was standing by its
1985 guidelines forbidding British sales of ``lethal equipment'' to
either Iran or Iraq.
   Although the two nations' 8-year-old war was stopped by a
U.N.-mediated cease-fire last year, negotiations so far have failed
to produce a permanent peace treaty.
   ``It's not going ahead,'' the ministry spokeswoman said of the
deal. She refused to elaborate.
   The British Aerospace Hawk trainer aircraft is used for flight
and weapons training and can be modified for ground attack
purposes, said the company.
</TEXT>
