<FIRST>r a PM-BoarderSlayings     07-29 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boarder Slayings,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Boarder Killed Two, Commits Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHESTER, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reclusive and chronically ill boarder is
suspected of killing his landlady and her daughter, then living for
a week or more in the same house with their bodies before killing
himself, police said.
   When police climbed through a window at the house Thursday
night, a shot rang out from an upstairs bedroom. They found the
body of a man who had just shot himself with a small caliber gun,
police said Friday.
   Police searched the house and found the bodies of two females,
both badly decomposed, in the basement. Autopsies performed Friday
by the chief state medical examiner's office indicated that the
women, Jarmila Petrzelka, believed to be in her early 70s, and her
daughter, Jana Petrzelka, in her early 40, both died of gunshot
wounds to the head.
   The man found upstairs, identified as William ``Red'' Hewitt,
died of a self-inflicted gunshot wound, medical examiners said.
   Friends and neighbors described Hewitt as a reclusive,
chronically ill boarder who had lived with the Petrzelkas for about
four years but was no longer wanted in the house. When he moved in,
friends said, he was dating the younger Petrzelka, a social worker,
but the relationship had long since ended.
   ``Over the past couple of years, they hadn't been very happy
with him staying there, but they were not the kind of people who
would turn somebody out,'' said David Anderson, a friend of the
family.
</TEXT>
