<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-29 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEQUIM, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The skunk that broke into Eva Busch's house
several nights last week had a thing for her TV set.
   While Eva slept, the skunk would nose through her towels, shoes
and socks and gather them in front of the television. It couldn't
have been that much of a thrill to watch, she says, because the set
was off.
   ``For some reason or another he seemed to be interested in TV,''
she said.
   When she entered the bathroom Thursday morning, the skunk was in
the tub, and she called the police.
   Officer Ron Carter filled the tub with water, then scooped the
skunk up in a box and took him outside.
   ``Floating around in the tub, it couldn't spray me,'' Carter
said.
   Ms. Busch figures the animal entered through a back door left
open because of warm weather.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager is bounding off to set a new
world record with his pogo stick, and hopes to raise $5,000 to help
homeless people rebound.
   Bill Anzelc, 18, plans Aug. 12 to break the world pogo jumping
distance record of 11.53 miles.
   He has already has worn out a pogo stick practicing for the
attempt. During a recent practice, he covered 4.8 miles in slightly
more than than two hours.
   ``When I was 9 or 10, I did like 700 jumps on a pogo stick, so I
figured I could beat the record,'' he said.
   Anzelc learned from the Guinness Book of World Records in London
he can have five minutes of rest per hour during the hop.
   A pogo stick manufacturer in New York has offered to donate
several pogo sticks for Anzelc's attempt.
   The teen-ager is collecting pledges, and proceeds will go to the
Center for the Homeless.
   The current pogo record is held by Ashrita Furman of New York
City, who bopped up and down the foothills of Mount Fuji, Japan,
for eight hours on Jan. 8, 1986.
   Furman also made 3,647 jumps on a pogo stick in 8{ feet of the
Amazon River of Peru on Jan. 11, 1987. With each jump, his head
came above the surface and he breathed through a mask and snorkel.
</TEXT>
