<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SKorea-China 1stLd-Writethru a0453 07-29 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SKorea-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Army Colonel And Embassy Attache Defect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with defense ministry confirming
defections, other detail; CORRECTs defector's rank and spelling of name;
picks up 12th pvs, ``Newspapers in ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese army officer and his wife
defected today to South Korea through the demilitarized zone
separating the country from communist North Korea, the defense
ministry said.
   Meanwhile, newspapers in Tokyo reported today that a Chinese
Embassy attache, protected by the Japanese government while she
sought asylum, left to start a new life in West Germany.
   Ma Qiuyun, an attache in the embassy's visa section, went into
hiding after the June 3-4 military crackdown on pro-democracy
protesters in Beijing and sought help from the Japanese government
June 14, Yomiuri Shimbun newspaper said.
   It was not known immediately whether the defectors from North
Korea seek asylum for the same reason.
   A South Korean intelligence source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, identified the officer as Maj. Zuo Xiukai, 40, a member
of the Chinese delegation to the Korean Military Armistice
Commission that oversees the 1953 Korean cease-fire.
   Zuo is the fourth-ranking officer in the Chinese delegation led
by a brigadier general, he said.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Brig. Gen. Yoon Chang-ro said the
Chinese couple remain in protective custody of the American-led
U.N. Command after walking across the border through Panmunjom
truce village this morning.
   The senior official, from the government National Unification
Board, did not say whether the defectors seek asylum in South Korea
or a third country such as Taiwan. Seoul has no diplomatic
relations with Beijing, but relations between the two recently have
improved.
   The official, requesting anonymity, said the Chinese couple will
be handed over to South Korea soon.
   The U.N. Command which polices Panmunjom consists of
representatives of the United States and 15 other countries that
helped South Korea drive out invading North Koreans in the 1950-53
Korean War.
   China fought with North Korea and signed the 1953 cease-fire.
   Today's defection is the first known Chinese defection through
Panmunjom. North Koreans, Russians and Czechoslovakians have
defected there.
   Newspapers in Tokyo reported it took the Japanese government a
month to to find a country to shelter Ms. Ma, 27. Finally, West
Germany agreed and Lufthansa German airline confirmed she flew to
Frankfurt Friday afternoon.
   According to Mainichi Shimbun newspaper, Ms. Ma's first
preference was the United States, but Washington refused,
apparently to avoid worsening relations strained since the U.S.
Embassy in Beijing began protecting Chinese dissident Fang Lizhi
and his wife, physics professor Li Shuxian. Australia also turned
down Ms. Ma, the Tokyo Shimbun said.
   U.S. Embassy officials could not be reached for comment today
and the newspaper account could not be verified.
   The Bush administration has offered protection to all Chinese
citizens in the United States and at least two Chinese diplomats
have obtained refuge in the country. In June, a State Department
spokesman said other Chinese officials have asked Washington for
protection, but he refused to elaborate.
   Fang and Ms. Li fled to the U.S. Embassy after Chinese troops
marched on unarmed protesters in Beijing and killed hundreds,
perhaps thousands. China says only 100 civilians and nearly 100
soldiers and police died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
