<DOCNO> AP890729-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0711EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     07-29 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Die in Latest Violence; Police Say One-Sixth of Population
Has Fled</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MOHAMMED SALAM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces kept up their
relentless rocket attacks in Beirut today, killing eight people and
wounding 42 in a wave of bloodshed that has driven out all but a
fraction of the populace, police said.
   Fires blazed out of control and palls of thick, black smoke
billowed from gaping holes that rockets and shells made in
apartment buildings in both Moslem and Christian sectors.
   The new casualties raised the overall toll to 502 killed and
2,056 wounded in the 19-week confrontation between Christian forces
and Syrian army gunners.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under regulations,
estimated that only about 250,000 people remain in the city that
was home to an estimated 1.5 million residents when the current
fighting broke out March 8.
   The spokesman said about 50 percent of the population fled in
the first three months of the fighting and about 350,000 people
have fled in the past 10 days.
   Most of Beirut's residents have fled to south Lebanon, the
eastern Bekaa valley and the mountain resorts northeast of the city
to escape the deadly shelling duels, the spokesman said.
   Moslem and Christian radio stations interrupted regular
programming early in the day to report that shelling duels were
continuing across a mountain range southeast of the capital.
   ``The fight started very early today,'' the Moslem-run Voice of
the Nation radio reported in a news flash.
   The Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon radio urged civilians
to ``take maximum precaution because the shelling might escalate
and spread to other areas.''
   The thuds of exploding shells echoed across the wooded hills
south of Beirut early in the day as Syrian army gunners pounded the
Christian suburb of Baabda east of the capital.
   Baabda houses the presidential palace that has been used as the
main headquarters for Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun
since the confrontation broke out.
   Several motorists, heading to Beirut to inspect their deserted
apartments and businesses, turned back to south Lebanon and other
safe areas to avoid being caught in the cross-fire.
   ``They're shelling his palace. He'll respond soon. I don't want
to be around when his response starts,'' said Marwan Shaar, a Sunni
Moslem who owns a money exchange company.
   Shaar spoke in the Syrian-policed Khaldeh area, seven miles
south of Beirut. The area was under fierce shelling from Aoun's
gunners overnight.
   The escalating shelling duels coincided with reports in
Lebanon's heated rumor mill that either Aoun or the Syrians would
have to storm their opponent's positions to break out of the
4-month shelling duel that has not altered either side's areas of
influence.
   Aoun, in an interview with the weekly Arab and International
An-Nahar, pledged that ``We shall be advancing against the occupied
areas.'' He did not elaborate.
   The 54-year-old Maronite general had declared a ``war of
liberation'' against Syria's 40,000 troops deployed in
predominantly Moslem sections of Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the Arab League.
   He made the move after the Syrians and allied forces besieged
his 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of Beirut in
retaliation for his blockade of ports run by Syrian-backed militias
south of the capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890729-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 2ndLd-Writethru a0452 07-29 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0452,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Troops To Start Withdrawal Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with new casualty figures; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said thousands of
Indian troops would begin leaving today, the second anniversary of
an accord that brought them to Sri Lanka to quell a rebellion but
instead fueled more violence.
   India agreed on Friday to resume withdrawing its 45,000
peacekeeping troops, averting a showdown with Sri Lanka President
Ranasinghe Premadasa, who had called the continued troop presence a
threat to his country's independence.
   The government said 3,000 to 4,000 troops would begin leaving
today.
   ``The Indo-Sri Lanka problem to a great extent has been
resolved,'' Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne said before he and a
six-member delegation left for New Delhi to discuss a timetable for
the withdrawal of the rest of the Indian troops.
   ``India's decision to recommence the withdrawal process has
further consolidated the 2,500-year-old friendship between the two
countries,'' he said.
   Premadasa originally sought the departure of all Indian troops
by today, but India maintained an immediate withdrawal would worsen
ethnic violence.
   India's decision Friday came on one of the most violent days,
when 74 people were killed.
   Casualties included nine Tamil guerrillas killed Friday in two
separate clashes with Indian troops, according to military
officials who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   State television said most victims were killed by Sri Lankan
forces in the Sinhalese heartland, where extremists have violently
protested government peace efforts and where Indian forces are not
deployed.
   The military also announced at least 150 people have died since
the government declared a nationwide curfew from midnight Thursday
to 6 a.m. Sunday to prevent violence during the anniversary.
   The two-year Indian military presence has fueled ethnic violence
among Tamil guerrillas the Indians were supposed to disarm and
Sinhalese extremists who say the Indian presence violates Sri
Lankan sovereignty.
   India, spurred by its own politically powerful Tamil ethnic
minority of 60 million, sent troops to Sri Lanka to enforce a July
29, 1987, peace accord sponsored by India and designed to give
ethnic Tamils some autonomy in northern and eastern Sri Lanka.
   But the biggest Tamil guerrilla group, the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam, reneged and began attacking the Indians.
   Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who comprise
75 percent of the population and control the government and armed
forces.
   Sinhalese extremists upset with the concessions made to Tamils,
meanwhile, began attacking moderate Sinhalese who supported the
peace overtures.
   Sinhalese radicals are accused of killing 4,000 people, mostly
Sinhalese government officials and supporters, since Indian troops
began arriving.
   Another 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have
died in the Tamil separatist war that started in 1983.
   In Washington, the Bush administration said it hopes New Delhi's
decision saves lives.
   ``We welcome this development and hope that India and Sri Lanka
will be successful in reaching an agreement on a timetable for
withdrawal that minimizes bloodshed while recognizing Sri Lanka's
sovereignty and independence,'' said State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler.
   It remained unclear when all of the Indian troops would leave.
Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne and six other Sri Lankan
officials were to fly to New Delhi on Friday to discuss a timetable
for the withdrawal of the rest of the Indian troops.
   Premadasa earlier said Sri Lankan troops would leave the
barracks where they have been confined for two years and resume
patrols in Tamil areas.
   At the peak of its involvement in Sri Lanka, India's
peacekeeping force numbered at least 70,000. The most recent
withdrawals were in January and February when about 5,000 soldiers
left shortly after Premadasa took office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
