<FIRST>r a PM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0475 07-29 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Blaze Destroys Three Houses; Idaho Forests Burn On</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with acreage figure, lower official
number evacuated to 2,500, sted 3,500; picks up 4th graf, `One of ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Brush fires in California torched houses and forced the
evacuation of several communities, and Idaho's governor declared a
state of extreme emergency to handle the blazes consuming thousands
of acres of forest.
   A fast-moving fire roared through a windy tinderbox of dry grass
and brush in the Sierra Nevada foothills today, and Sheriff's Lt.
Greg Burton of Fresno County, Calif., said at least three homes had
been destroyed, with 1,500 firefighters unable to control the
3,000-acre fire.
   At least 2,500 residents were evacuated from the communities of
New Auberry, Meadow Lakes, Alder Springs, Bald Mountain and Jose
Basin, said Bob Kutz, spokesman for the California Department of
Forestry. About 150 nursing home patients were among those taken to
a local high school in the area 190 miles east of San Francisco.
   One of the evacuees, Fred Burnham, had moved to the highland
area from low-lying Fresno just a day before the fire _ to escape
the heat.
   When a sheriff's deputy screamed at him to clear out of his new
house, Burnham said, ``I never even came out with a shirt.''
   Elsewhere in central California, firefighters saved at least a
dozen homes from a fire that burned 10,500 acres near the city of
Atascadero.
   ``Miraculously, all those homes have been spared,'' California
Department of Forestry spokesman Ron Alsop said. ``The flames
burned right up to them.''
   About 750 firefighters had the blaze 40 percent contained early
today. Officials refused to estimate when it might be fully
contained, although increasing humidity and low overnight
temperatures were a boon to firefighters, Alsop said.
   The blaze destroyed 15 to 20 outbuildings, including barns and
corrals. Owners moved animals from some ranches in the area about
175 miles north of Los Angeles.
   In the Los Angeles area community of Walnut, firefighters
surrounded a fast-moving brush fire that had threatened several
homes and the nearby California Polytechnical Institute in Pomona,
officials said.
   Campus police evacuated 800 students as the fire approached,
said Rafael Ortiz, a firefighter with the Los Angeles County Fire
Department, but the blaze was contained about 8:30 p.m. and
students were allowed back into their dorm rooms on the campus 30
miles east of downtown Los Angeles.
   In Idaho, Gov. Cecil Andrus authorized military reinforcements
Friday to join the battle against hundreds of forest fires. His
emergency proclamation allows the state to use the National Guard.
   The Boise Interagency Fire Center estimated some 3,000 people
were fighting Idaho fires or supporting suppression efforts against
smaller blazes.
   More than 15,000 acres had been blackened by an estimated 500
fires, although a number of blazes were controlled by late Friday.
   ``Fires are continuing to pop up,'' Payette National Forest
spokesman Dave Olson said. ``It's going to be a long weekend for
us.''
   The top-priority fire in the state was the 1,500-acre Fleming
Creek blaze, with towering smoke columns visible 50 miles south in
Boise. One lane of traffic on Idaho Highway 55 was closed over a
two-mile section to guard against falling rocks and burning timber.
</TEXT>
