<FIRST>r i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru   07-29 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0478,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Jails Protesters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to ADD details, comment from opposition. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military tribunal has sentenced seven
youths to five-year prison terms for staging anti-government
demonstrations, a government newspaper said today.
   Also today, a spokesman for the main opposition party, the
National League for Democracy, said as many as 1,500 people have
been arrested since the second week of July. He asked not to be
identified by name.
   Police arrested the seven youths for shouting slogans July 17 at
Rangoon's Shwedagon Pagoda Buddhist temple on a religious holiday
and sentenced them Friday, the Working People's Daily said. It gave
few other details.
   On Tuesday, a military tribunal ordered the death sentence for
three young members of the National League for Democracy who were
convicted of planting a package bomb that killed two people at a
government oil refinery on July 7. A Western diplomat today called
Tuesday's proceedings ``a real show trial.''
   ``They say that the prosecution was heard and the exhibits were
shown, but the outside world hasn't seen anything,'' said the
diplomat in Rangoon, who spoke by telephone to the AP in Bangkok on
condition of anonymity.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights
organization, also criticized the sentences.
   ``According to the United Nations, executions resulting from
summary procedures denying the right of legal appeal and omitting
other fair safeguards constitute `the arbitrary deprivation of
life,'' it said in a statement received in Rangoon today.
   Burma's military government recently has intensified its
crackdown on the political opposition while releasing common
criminals under an amnesty announced July 20. Today's Working
Peoples Daily said 7,326 prisoners have been freed under the order.
   Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo, leaders of the National League for
Democracy, were placed under house arrest on July 20. A goverment
spokesman later accused them of trying to ``destroy the military
and create anarchy in the country.'' The government denies Ms. Suu
Kyi is on a hunger strike in her Rangoon home.
   In Britain today, the Foreign Office expressed dismay at reports
that Ms. Suu Kyi is on a hunger strike. A Foreign Office spokesman
also said Britain ``deplored'' the failure of authorities to allow
British consuls to visit Dr. Michael Aris, who is Ms. Suu Kyi's
husband. Aris, who is British, has had his movements restricted
since he recently returned to Burma from Britain.
   The spokesman for the National League for Democracy said today
he could not confirm that Ms. Suu Kyi was on a hunger strike
because the party has been denied contact with her. The Western
diplomat said detailed reports reaching his embassy from reliable
sources indicate Ms. Suu Kyi is refusing food.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
