<FIRST>r a PM-Root 1stLd-Writethru a0482 07-29 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Root, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mystery Pilot Resting at Parents' Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS final graf to UPDATE with quote from Root refusing to comment
on lawsuit.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas L. Root, the lawyer who survived a
mysterious gunshot and an 800-mile flight and crash into the
Atlantic Ocean, is recovering from his injuries at his parents'
home here, his father said today.
   Thomas F. Root, the pilot's father, said that his son remembers
little of his July 13 flight and doesn't plan to talk to reporters
until ``his doctor tells him he is fit enough.''
   Root set out on a business trip from his home in Arlington, Va.,
to Rocky Mount, N.C., and later told air traffic controllers he was
having trouble breathing. He put his plane on autopilot and
military planes kept watch on him until his plane ran out of fuel
and ditched near the Bahamas.
   Root said he was unconscious until his plane hit the water and
did not know how he received a gunshot wound to the abdomen, which
doctors noticed after his rescue. He was released from a hospital
in Hollywood, Fla., on Monday.
   The reason for his illness during the flight and the source of
the wound remain as much a mystery to Root as they are to those who
have investigated his flight, Root's father told The Columbus
Dispatch.
   ``He says it's not a story, it's just what happened,'' he said.
   During his convalesence in this town 55 miles southeast of
Cleveland, Root has visited the family doctor for treatment of a
collapsed lung and seen the family dentist, but otherwise has
stayed at home, his father said.
   Root was sued Thursday in federal court in New Orleans by a
group of investors who tried to get an Federal Communications
Commission license in 1987 to build an FM radio station. They claim
his actions cost them $125,000.
   Root specialized in that type of litigation. But the lawsuit
claims he committed legal malpractice by lying about some things,
failing to attend to details associated with getting a license, and
keeping the investors from getting a cash settlement from another
group that ultimately got the license.
   ``I don't care to comment,'' Root told The Associated Press when
asked about the suit today.
</TEXT>
