<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Robbery     07-29 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Robbery,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged in Big British Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities charged a 57-year-old man Saturday in
connection with one of Britain's biggest cash robberies, the 1983
theft of nearly $10 million from a security company's headquarters,
police said.
   The suspect, Frederick Foreman, was extradited from Spain on
Friday.
   He appeared Saturday before magistrates at London's Bow Street
court and was ordered jailed pending his next court appearance
Friday, said Scotland Yard. He did not apply for bail.
   A police spokeswoman said he was charged with taking part in the
robbery.
   The robbery occurred in April 1983 at the London headquarters of
Security Express, a firm specializing in moving cash and bullion.
   Four other men were convicted in London in June 1985 for their
part in the robbery.
   Spanish authorities have been attempting to expel several other
Britons living in Spain and suspected of involvement.
</TEXT>
