<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Ireland-Drownings     07-29 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Ireland-Drownings,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four British Students Drown off Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARAN ISLAND, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dinghy taking six British college
students capsized and sank in stormy seas, drowning four students,
police and witnesses said.
   One survivor, 22-year-old John Whitting, said he spent three
hours swimming after the accident early Friday. He said he finally
arrived back at Aran Island.
   ``Death seemed very close at hand,'' he said. ``But I did not
want to stop. I was very lucky.''
   The vacationing students had spent Thursday on Aran Island, one
mile off County Donegal in northwestern Ireland. At the time of the
accident, they were taking a late-night trip to Iochtar Island.
   The second survivor, Natasha Martineau, was rescued by a
lifeboat after Whitting reached shore and alerted authorities. She
said she struggled for hours to keep another woman afloat but lost
sight of her minutes before the lifeboat arrived.
   The victims all were undergraduates at Edinburgh University.
They included Matthew Hallifax, whose father, Sir David Hallifax,
is governor of Windsor Castle, Queen Elizabeth II's residence.
</TEXT>
