<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan Bjt   07-29 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan, Bjt,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rains Arrive Before Relief, Threatening Another Year of Starvation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rainy season has hit southern Sudan,
and a relief operation intended to get food to the region is behind
schedule and hindered by soggy roads and fears of rebel attacks.
   In Kosti south of Khartoum, 17,500 tons of emergency supplies
are just now being loaded on Nile River barges that were to have
gone south weeks ago.
   Boxcars loaded with 1,350 tons of other supplies are parked in a
railroad yard, immovable for fear the train will be attacked by
rebels or starving peasants, as previous ones were.
   While nearly three-fourths of the targeted 105,000 tons reached
redistribution points before the rains, which will make them
inaccessible, relief workers say pockets of potential starvation
remain in southern Sudan, an area the size of Texas.
   ``One cannot speak of a disaster for the moment, but some of
these areas will have trouble,'' said Francis Junod of the
International Committee of the Red Cross. ``The extent depends on
the ecological situation and the peace talks.''
   Operation Lifeline Sudan, coordinated by the United Nations and
using trucks, trains and barges, was to have provided enough
supplies to help people displaced by the southern civil war survive
the summer monsoon-like rains.
   Officials report that 72,000 tons have been moved. The Red Cross
mounted a smaller airborne operation that failed to meet its goal,
transporting 6,000 tons of a planned 7,000 to 8,000 tons.
   ``The situation in the rebel-held territories is a bit tricky,''
Junod said. ``We've not been able to send in enough food because of
the onset of the rains.''
   Trucks and trains are virtually useless in the rainy season.
Neither the railroad bed nor the roads in the south, mostly rutted
pathways, are constructed well enough to withstand the downpours.
   In 1988, U.N. officials say 250,000 southerners died of
starvation, flood or disease during the rainy season. The estimate
of some Western relief workers is twice that.
   Both U.N. and other relief officials said Operation Lifeline had
to succeed to save 100,000 people from starving to death this
summer.
   Some relief workers in this wretchedly poor country, Africa's
largest with only a tiny network of roads and railways, blame
mismanagement and lack of clear planning for the failure of both
the U.N. and Red Cross efforts to reach their goals, despite the
huge expenditures.
   The Red Cross airlift cost $35 million from December, when it
began, to June.
   Operation Lifeline Sudan, which began April 1, was scheduled to
cost $132 million, which donors pledged at a March conference in
Khartoum. James P. Grant, the U.N. secretary-general's special
representative for the project, announced in mid-July a need for an
additional $40 million. With previous increases, that brought the
total to $200 million.
   Both sides in the civil war generally have honored a cease-fire
since May, but unknown gunmen have attacked relief trucks and
trains, with 11 people killed and several boxcars looted.
   A 45-car train loaded with 1,350 tons of relief supplies was to
have left July 17 from Babanousa in southern Kordofan, north of the
war zone, en route to Aweil, a major center for displaced people in
the south.
   Days later, a U.N. official said the train would not leave
without assurances from the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army
that it would not be attacked. The train is to carry food and
medicines to places held by both the rebels and the government.
   Politics also have interfered with the relief operation.
Operations were suspended temporarily after a military coup June 30
ousted the civilian government of Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi.
The United Nations' Grant said the new leader, Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan
el-Bashir, ``took great pains to reaffirm the support of the new
government to continuing Operation Lifeline Sudan.''
   The government previously put obstacles in the way, claiming
agencies wanted to feed rebels trying to take over Sudan.
   Rebel commanders also have used food as a weapon, even shooting
at relief planes flying into rebel areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
