<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Norway-Opium     07-29 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Norway-Opium,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opium Poppies Bloom Near Hospital for Drug Addicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's largest illegal poppy field
has been discovered near a hospital that treats drug addicts, news
reports said Saturday.
   About 1,000 opium-producing poppies, used to make heroin and
morphine, were found Friday after a nurse, not realizing what they
were, picked some to decorate a room at Oslo's Gaustad Hospital,
the Verdens Gang daily newspaper reported.
   Another nurse recognized the flowers and called police, who
destroyed the well-tended field, said the paper.
   Chief nurse Anne-Lise Bergenheim told the paper that the
hospital patients, who are closely supervised, could not have
tended the field ``unless they worked at night wearing miners'
lamps.''
   The flowers usually grow in warmer climates, but they can also
thrive during Norway's short growing season.
   Police said they had no idea who planted the flowers.
</TEXT>
