<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1157EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-Chicken     07-29 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Chicken,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush And Democrats Working On Savings And Loan Bailout</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and congressional Democrats are
engaged in a game of chicken over how to finance the
multibillion-dollar bailout of hundreds of failed savings
institutions.
   On Friday, the squawking began.
   Bush and members of Congress paraded before television cameras
at three separate news conferences to outline their views, one day
after House and Senate negotiators sealed a compromise deal on the
landmark legislation.
   The president favors a complex scheme to pay for the bailout by
borrowing the money through a new, quasi-private agency. That has
the advantage of keeping $50 billion in S&amp;L spending out of the
budget deficit, which, if it goes too high, triggers automatic
spending cuts under the Gramm-Rudman law.
   Democrats support the plan adopted by the House-Senate
conference, which they say is cheaper and more honest, to borrow
the money through the Treasury Department. However, that would
balloon the deficit over the next three years. Democrats evade the
automatic spending cuts by simply waiving Gramm-Rudman.
   Republicans say the administration's method keeps the spending
discipline of Gramm-Rudman in place. Democrats say Bush is just
engaging in a more subtle kind of subterfuge.
   Both agree that the other side is holding up urgent legislation
needed to staunch the industry's hemorrhaging and neither wants to
be blamed for that.
   The stakes are high. S&amp;Ls are losing an estimated $20 million a
day, $833,333 an hour, $13,888 a minute and $231.48 a second.
That's a lot of blame to shoulder and it hardly seems worth it for
either side to get tarred over what at first glance seems like
nothing more than an accounting question.
   But, the issue is important, not now, but over the next several
years, because it will have a major role in the annual jousting
over how to balance the budget, through spending cuts or tax
increases.
   Even though both plans alleviate the danger of an automatic
spending cut, politically, their effect couldn't be more different.
   Democrats are betting that if they win on S&amp;L spending, and the
reported budget deficit approaches the record set during the Reagan
years instead of getting better, Bush won't be willing to endure
the kind of drastic spending cuts that would be needed to reduce it.
   They believe he will feel that much more pressure to abandon his
``Read my lips: No new taxes'' pledge repeated over and over during
the 1988 campaign.
   The issue comes to a head this week when the S&amp;L compromise
package reaches the full House and Senate, which must approve it
before it goes to Bush for his signature.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, has vowed ``unless God palsies my
voice'' to protect the deficit-reduction law that bears his name.
Gramm has the signatures of 41 senators, including his own,
pledging to reject the S&amp;L compromise. Under the Senate's rules,
that's enough to block it.
   On the other hand, if Gramm is successful the legislation
bounces back to the House-Senate conference, where majority
Democrats prevail.
   So, the two sides are locked in a stalemate. Either can tie up
the legislation, but neither has the stomach to do that for very
long.
   The winner likely will be the side that is most successful at
blaming the other for delay. Expect the squawking to grow louder.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dave Skidmore has covered the savings and loan crisis for The
Associated Press since 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890729-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Unemployment Bjt   07-29 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Unemployment, Bjt,0863</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jobless Level Climbs, Unrest Threatened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM RON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEROHAM, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An economic slump since the Palestinian
uprising and the government's increased interest in the occupied
lands have left this desert town and others like it with soaring
unemployment and the threat of unrest.
   ``It has become a catastrophe. Unemployment is a time bomb in
this town,'' said Rahel Messika, director of the government
employment agency in Yeroham, a cluster of neglected tenements
housing 7,000 people in the Negev Desert, 90 miles south of
Jerusalem.
   Analysts say high unemployment in small towns may cause tension
between rich and poor and between Jews of European and Middle
Eastern origin. It also could harden anti-Arab sentiment among
Israeli Jews who believe Palestinians working for lower wages are
stealing their jobs.
   In Yeroham, the only activity at mid-morning on a summer weekday
is at the unemployment office, where the jobless come looking for
work they know does not exist. Idle, middle-aged men seek relief in
the shade next to empty cafes and grocery stores.
   Yeroham was founded in the 1950s to house impoverished
immigrants as part of an effort by the late Prime Minister David
Ben-Gurion to develop the Negev Desert.
   The town has relied on a bottle factory and two metalworks. But
the plants have laid off 150 of the town's 2,000 workers, and
unemployment is officially pegged at 10 percent.
   ``At least an additional 10 percent don't bother to register any
more. They know no new offers have come in,'' Messika said.
   Young people recently demobilized from the army are leaving
Yeroham, hoping to find work and a more vigorous lifestyle in
cities such as Tel Aviv.
   The unemployment problem in such towns has become a major focus
of concern in Israel, taking precedence in newspapers over the
19-month Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied
lands.
   Last month, mayors of 30 development towns chained themselves to
a fence outside Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's office to press
demands for economic aid.
   The 9.7 percent jobless figure for May was a 20-year high for
the Jewish state. The government estimates that the June figure
will break a record 10 percent.
   Ruth Klinov, a labor relations expert at Hebrew University in
Jerusalem, said the Palestinian uprising, which has disrupted the
construction industry and badly hurt tourism, contributed 2 percent
to the overall unemployment rate.
   The Histadrut, Israel's trade union federation, organized a
two-hour nationwide strike by 1.2 million workers to protest
unemployment in late July. Experts say more strikes may be in the
offing.
   ``There is a great potential for violence in unemployment, which
may eventually be directed against the Histadrut itself if they
don't get results,'' said Noah Levin-Epstein, a sociologist at Tel
Aviv University.
   One sign of the unrest was a wildcat strike by 50 laid-off
employees of the Urdan metalworks in Netanya, which builds Israel's
main battle tank, the Merkava. The workers held their managers
hostage four hours to protest the dismissal orders.
   Klinov said as long as the government refuses to bail out
private companies and maintains a policy of privatizing state-owned
companies, ``an unemployment rate of at least 10 percent is here to
stay.''
   In an effort to halt the growth of unemployment, Israel's
Cabinet approved $137.5 million to help create new jobs, especially
in development towns.
   Like other development towns, Yeroham was built around light
industries and was heavily subsidized. But in recent years the
government has cut back support and diverted funds to develop
settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which got $150 million
last year.
   The result is an economic slowdown that has affected everyone
from grocery stores to banks.
   Shalom Benvinisti, 35, an immigrant from Morocco, lost his job
as a bank teller five years ago and has worked temporary jobs to
support his diabetic wife and three children.
   Even temporary work vanished two months ago, and he now relies
on unemployment benefits of $450 a month. After six months, the
benefit will be cut in half.
   ``My kids know that we can't buy them new clothes or the proper
school books. but they are good about it. They don't complain. They
understand how hard it is,'' he said.
   Benvinisti took a government-run training course, learning to
make metal frames for concrete casting. But he still cannot find a
job because ``they all want years of experience.''
   Yoav Peled, a political scientist at Tel Aviv University, said a
survey of 832 Israelis in eight development towns indicated high
unemployment has increased support for extreme anti-Arab parties.
   ``They feel that the Palestinians are forcing wages down and are
stealing their jobs,'' said Peled said.
   Unemployment is also high among 800,000 Arabs with Israeli
citizenship. In predominantly Arab Nazareth, the official jobless
rate is 10 percent with an additional 12 percent unregistered,
according to city spokesman Fahoum Safwan.
   ``High unemployment among Arab-Israelis will strengthen their
growing identification with the Palestinian uprising, as economic
frustrations are added to political tensions,'' Levin-Epstein said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
