<FIRST>r a AM-Catholics-Racism     07-29 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catholics-Racism,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Says Racism Permeates Catholic Church in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Racism permeates the Roman Catholic Church in
the United States, several clerics said, warning that more blacks
could follow the lead of a priest who set up an unauthorized
African American congregation.
   Seven black church leaders, speaking Friday after a national
conference of black clergy, called on the church to address the
needs of minorities and move blacks to positions of authority.
   ``The church has bought into the racist practices of the
American culture,'' said the Rev. Victor Cohea, a pastor from New
Orleans.
   The news conference at Marquette University followed a joint
conference of the National Black Catholic Clergy Caucus, the
National Black Sisters Conference and the National Black Catholic
Seminarians Association.
   Much discussed was the case of the Rev. George A. Stallings, a
Washington, D.C., priest who was suspended for setting up an
independent African-American congregation without permission of his
archbishop.
   The Rev. Albert J. McKnight of Opelousas, La., warned that
others could follow Stallings' lead.
   ``We're ready to take up the cross and commit ourselves to
change. I'm firmly convinced you're going to see changes,''
McKnight said.
   ``There are some of us who are ready to do exactly what George
Stallings did,'' he said.
   Responding to the criticism, the Rev. Joseph Perry, judicial
vicar of the Milwaukee Archdiocese and a member of the clergy
caucus, said he believed ``those comments would be rather strong
from my perspective.''
   Over the last 50 years, the Catholic Church has reached out to
various minority groups, Perry said.
   ``In my association with many black priests, I find them
extremely loyal to the church and willing to work with the system
for steady and certain improvement,'' he said.
   Sister Patricia Haley of Philadelphia said the church must
include minority group members and women at the highest
decision-making levels of its dioceses.
   ``The manner in which we do business is essentially a racist
system, and we've got to change the system,'' the sister said.
</TEXT>
