<FIRST>r w AM-VeepMansion     07-29 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Veep Mansion,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Adds Funds for Vice President's Mansion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee tacked an extra $200,000 on
next year's appropriation for care of the government mansion
occupied by Vice President Dan Quayle as the result of some sharp
lobbying by his wife, the Congressional Quarterly reported Saturday.
   When Marilyn Quayle decided she wanted to convert space on the
third floor into bedrooms for her three young children, she turned,
not to Budget Director Richard G. Darman, but to Aubrey A. ``Tex''
Gunnels, a powerful aide to the subcommittee which has funding
jurisdiction over the Executive Office of the President, the
magazine said.
   And that is why the $18.4 billion Treasury Department and Postal
Service spending bill approved Tuesday by the full House
Appropriations Committee contains $578,000 for the ``care,
maintenance and operation'' of the vice president's residence _
more than twice last year's figure and $200,000 more than requested
by the White House, the article said.
   Gunnels is staff director of the Appropriations subcommittee on
the Treasury, Postal Service and General Government, whose chairman
is Rep. Edward R. Roybal, D-Calif. Gunnels has worked on Capitol
Hill since 1958.
   The magazine said that at Marilyn Quayle's personal invitation,
the 71-year-old native of Lubbock, Texas, visited the mansion last
spring to review her plans for installing several new bedrooms and
a bath in a third-floor area now used for storage.
   Mrs. Quayle declined to comment on the visit, but her chief of
staff Denise Balzano, said that while the vice president's wife had
outlined her ideas for the space, she had made no formal request
for extra funds. In the wake of the House committee's action, ``It
looks like (Gunnels) has been helpful,'' Ms. Balzano said.
   Gunnels declined to discuss his role. ``Just say that the
committee was informed that the vice president's residence needs
some more bedrooms,'' he told the magazine.
   Roybal said that ``Had I gone out to see (the mansion), I would
have recommended it myself.''
   The 96-year-old Queen Anne-style residence is on the lush,
tree-lined grounds of the Naval Observatory, about two miles from
the White House. Formerly the quarters of the chief of naval
operations, it became the official residence of the vice president
in 1974.
</TEXT>
