<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 6thLd-Writethru a0532 07-29 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0532,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Resigns As Party Chief, Replaced by Rakowski</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Politburo members and party
secretaries sacked by the plenum. Pickup 3rd pvs, ``Jaruzelski, who...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski resigned
today as head of the Communist Party and was replaced by the
outgoing prime minister, a politician who has become a champion of
hard-line forces in the party.
   The moves came at a two-day Central Committee plenum called to
debate the future of the party, which has been deeply divided by
policy disputes and parliamentary elections in which many of its
candidates were trounced.
   The plenum also dropped five of the 18 Politburo members and
three of the nine party secretaries, the official news agency PAP
announced.
   Jaruzelski, who had led the party since 1981, promised to give
up his post as party chief before the National Assembly narrowly
elected him to the new office of president on July 19.
   But some observers were surprised that the Central Committee
elected outgoing Prime Minister Mieczyslaw Rakowski by a 4-1 margin
to replace Jaruzelski as party leader.
   The selection of the 62-year-old Rakowski culminated a
remarkable political rise by an official who only joined the
Politburo in December 1987 after having been dropped from the
government in 1985.
   In recent months Rakowski has been roundly criticized for his
government's handling of the economy. A party member with a long
reputation as a reformer, in the past year Rakowski has become the
champion of hard-line elements in the party and those concerned
about the rising influence of Solidarity.
   Earlier today, Rakowski's government came under renewed
criticism for its economic performance. Inflation has climbed into
triple digits and basic goods such as meat, bread and sugar have
been in short supply in recent weeks.
   A plan by Rakowski to sharply raise food prices Aug. 1 has been
criticized as not properly prepared.
   ``The Central Committee accepted with one abstention the
resignation of Wojciech Jaruzelski from the office of first
secretary,'' PAP said. Moments later, the plenum elected Rakowski
171 to 41, PAP said.
   The only remaining question facing the plenum, which began
Friday, appeared to be who will replace Rakowski as prime minister.
   Potential candidates appeared to be Politburo member Wladyslaw
Baka, Ireneusz Sekula, now deputy prime minister and a Rakowski
loyalist, or Roman Malinowski, the leader of the allied United
Peasant Party.
   Jaruzelski hinted at the plenum Friday that he would not hold
the party leadership much longer and said a full congress of the
2-million-member party should be held soon. ``I am standing before
you still, for the moment, in a double role,'' said Jaruzelski,
referring to his election as president.
   He challenged fellow Communists to decide ``what we stand for.''
   PAP said the plenum today adopted a resolution declaring the
party's willingness to work with the independent Solidarity trade
union movement and with the 260 Solidarity lawmakers chosen by the
voters in June.
   As a result of the country's most democratic elections since
World War II, the formerly banned Solidarity now controls 99 out of
100 seats in the new freely elected Senate and 161 of the 460 seats
in the Sejm, or parliament. Many party-backed candidates suffered
humiliating defeats in the election.
   The resolution reaffirmed the party's January decision to
legalize Solidarity and ``defined conditions'' needed to improve
the economy, PAP said, without elaborating.
   Earlier today, the party Central Committee information policy
director, Slawomir Tabkowski, told the plenum the party is changing
too quickly for more doctrinaire members, PAP said.
   ``The speaker said possibilities should be created for those who
are disappointed with the party ... and those who do not identify
with the direction of changes to leave,'' PAP said.
   But Jerzy Majka, the editor of the generally hard-line party
daily Trybuna Ludu, said recent talk about the party's future is
``unsettling to all people, not only party members,'' according to
PAP. Majka said the party must maintain its ``rational'' approach
in trying to solve Poland's problems.
   The discussion included sharp criticism of the party's
performance in the elections and of the government's handling of
the economy.
   In another development, Politburo member Wladyslaw Baka quit as
party secretary in charge of the economy after delivering a speech
criticizing Rakowski's administration. Rakowski handed in his
government's resignation when the new Parliament was seated. Baka
was considered a likely candidate to succeed Rakowski as prime
minister.
</TEXT>
