<DOCNO> AP890729-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1337EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     07-29 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Says He Does Not Approve of `Great Democracy'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping said in an essay
publicized Saturday that he does not approve of ``great democracy''
but that ``small democracy'' is needed to keep in touch with the
masses.
   Allowing the masses to supervise the rulers ``is better than not
having supervision,'' wrote the 84-year-old Deng, who has crushed
three populist democracy movements in his decade of rule.
   The last time was in June, when he ordered an army attack on
student protesters.
   ``If we don't accept supervision and expand the democratic life
of the party and country, we will be divorced from the masses and
commit great errors,'' Deng wrote in the essay summarized on the
television evening news.
   The report said the essay would appear in the next issue of the
magazine Party Building.
   Deng added, ``We do not approve of great democracy. Great
democracy is avoidable, and this requires having small democracy.''
   He did not explain what he meant by the terms, but ``great
democracy'' appeared to be a reference to the kind of unfettered
debate that Deng denounced in the recent student protests as
leading to anarchy. In past writings, he also has rejected
Western-style parliamentary democracy as bourgeois.
   By small democracy, he apparently was referring to controlled
expressions of opinion that do not challenge the power of the
Communist Party. He wrote that the party should be supervised by
the masses and by the eight officially approved non-Communist
parties that are permitted to exist.
   Most important, the party must police itself, he said.
   ``Whether or not the Communist Party is qualified to lead
depends on our party itself ... on our party's ideology and work
style,'' he wrote.
   The party, meanwhile, announced it was issuing a new book called
``Deng Xiaoping Over 28 Years,'' written by his colleagues and
commemorating his ``glorious and outstanding achievements.''
   Publication of the essay and the book were part of a new high
profile, tinged with adulation, for the aging leader, who had been
in semi-retirement.
   He re-emerged to lead the June crackdown on the student
protesters, and since then a series of books and a movie about him
have appeared. His name appears in newspaper headlines daily, and
millions of Chinese nationwide are being required to study a speech
he made on crushing the student ``rebellion.''
   Deng said in the past that he did not want the mass adulation
revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung received in his last years. The
current campaign of Dengist admiration falls far short of that, but
many Chinese have begun drawing a parallel.
   Deng had been expected to retire from his last official posts,
as head of the state and party military affairs commissions, later
this year. But Western diplomats say they consider that unlikely
given the army's new prominence and power.
   In other developments, Premier Li Peng told a French newspaper
publisher China is willing to maintain good relations with Paris
despite ``recent difficulties'' but that the future of relations
``depends on the French side.''
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Li spoke in a meeting with
Yang Yongju, publisher of Europe Times.
   France froze its relations with China to protest the crackdown
on the protesters, and China since has protested that France gave
refuge to some fugitive student and intellectual leaders.
</TEXT>
