<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1356EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Amoco-PolandOil     07-29 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amoco-Poland Oil,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amoco And Poland Sign Oil Exploration Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amoco Corp. has signed an agreement to explore
for oil in Poland, according to a published report.
   Under the contract, signed Friday in New York, Amoco and the
state-owned Polish Oil and Gas Co. will conduct a 12-month joint
study of geological and geophysical data on roughly 40 percent of
the country, the Chicago Tribune reported Saturday.
   If the exploration indicates potential oil reserves, Amoco and
Polish Oil and Gas would negotiate a second contract that would
enable the Chicago-based company to drill exploratory wells and
ultimately produce oil.
   Amoco Production Co. employees will go to Warsaw next month, and
Polish Oil and Gas employees will eventually come to the U.S.
production company's Houston headquarters to study the data.
   Amoco, the fifth-biggest U.S.-based energy company, has been
conducting a similar study in Yugoslavia.
   Poland produces only 3,000 barrels of oil a day, according to
Central Intelligence Agency estimates. By comparison, Illinois
pumps 63,000 barrels a day.
   Poland consumes an estimated 540,000 barrels of oil a day, much
of that obtained from the Soviet Union in exchange for machinery
and other goods.
   But the potential for oil is indicated by Poland's abundance of
coal _ the two hydrocarbons are often found in proximity to one
another.
   Poland hasn't explored intensively for oil for at least 45
years, and thus may have missed deposits detectable with today's
sophisticated equipment, said Alfred Munk, Amoco's manager of
foreign affairs.
   ``It's a problem of technical capabilities and money,'' said Jan
Szczurowski, the economic attache at the Polish commercial
consular's office in New York.
</TEXT>
