<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890729-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1422EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     07-29 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians And Christians Clash Across A Virtual Ghost City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners battled with
howitzers and rocket launchers Saturday over the ruins of a virtual
ghost city, deserted by more than a million people fleeing fighting
that has left hundreds dead.
   Police said eight people were killed and 42 wounded in overnight
and morning exchanges across the divided capital, where 1.5 million
people once lived.
   ``My city is dying. I'll die with it. I won't leave,'' Ihsan
Salam, a retired civil servant, said with tears in his eyes.
   ``I'll stay here. If I have to die, I'll die in dignity in my
apartment, in my bed. I don't want to live as a refugee,'' said the
70-year-old Sunni Moslem who lives in west Beirut's Zasrif district.
   The summer wind kicked up dust storms in the dirty streets, and
cats chased rats across piles of stinking garbage littering the
once-fashionable Hamra commercial thoroughfare.
   Banks, restaurants, stores and offices were closed, and the once
swarming streets were almost deserted. Fires blazed out of control
and palls of thick black smoke billowed from gaping holes in
apartment buildings.
   Salam is among only about 250,000 people still living in Beirut
after more than four months of almost daily artillery duels.
   Saturday's casualties raised the overall toll to 502 killed and
2,056 wounded in the 19-week confrontation between Christian army
commander Gen. Michel Aoun's troops and Syrian forces.
   The fighting erupted after Aoun imposed a naval blockade on
illegal ports run by Moslem militias south of Beirut in an effort
to recover around $100 million annually in lost customs revenues.
   The Syrians joined the Moslem militias shelling the Christian
enclave north of Beirut in retaliation and blocked its land
entrances.
   The Syrians, who consider Lebanon within their sphere of
influence, keep about 40,000 troops in predominantly Moslem areas
under a 1976 Arab League mandate to end the civil war, now in its
15th year.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
rules, said about half Beirut's population fled to safer areas in
the first three months of clashes.
   About 350,000 others deserted the capital during the past 10
days during a devastating bombardment of residential districts, he
said.
   Most evacuees headed to south Lebanon, the eastern Bekaa valley
and summer resorts in mountains northeast of the capital.
   The thuds of exploding shells echoed across the wooded hills
south of Beirut early in the day as Syrian army gunners pounded the
Christian suburb of Baabda east of the capital.
   Baabda houses the presidential palace where Aoun has his
residence and headquarters.
   Several motorists, heading to Beirut to inspect their deserted
apartments and businesses, turned back to avoid being caught in
cross fire.
   ``They're shelling his palace. He'll respond soon. I don't want
to be around when his response starts,'' said Marwan Shaar, a Sunni
who owns a currency trading company.
   He was speaking in the Syrian-policed Khaldeh area, seven miles
south of Beirut. The area came under fierce shelling overnight by
Christian gunners.
   The police spokesman said ``thousands'' of people were spending
nights in cars on river banks and seaside boulevards in south
Lebanon, because they couldn't find accommodations or couldn't
afford sky-high rents.
   Hundreds of children played in the Awali river just outside
Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut. Their parents slept in cars or on
mattresses and blankets on the river bank.
   ``At least it is safe here,'' said Samir Shatilla, a salesman
for an appliance company in west Beirut.
   Shatilla said he was spending the nights with his wife and two
sons in his old brown Plymouth.
</TEXT>
