<DOCNO> AP890729-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1429EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     07-29 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chileans Show Little Interest in Constitutional Referendum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unprecedented show of unity, both
the military government and its political foes are encouraging
Chileans to approve democratic reforms of the constitution in a
referendum Sunday.
   Most Chileans, however, have shown little interest in the vote,
apparently believing the changes will pass even with a small
turnout.
   Voting is mandatory, but government officials and opposition
leaders still fear many of the 7.6 million registered voters will
stay home.
   President Augusto Pinochet has sent all 16 of his Cabinet
ministers on tours of provincial cities to explain the proposed
reforms and ask people to vote.
   The head of the National Electoral Service, Juan Garcia, warned
that those failing to vote will be prosecuted and may be fined
$100. That's a lot of money in a country where about a third of the
labor force earns the legal mimimum salary of $66 a month or less.
   The referendum asks Chileans to approve or reject as a package
54 changes in the 1980 constitution, which was written by the
military.
   The changes include easing restrictions on Marxist activity,
which has been banned.
   It dilutes the government's power in the Senate by increasing
the number of seats from 36 to 48 and leaving the
government-appointed bloc at nine. It also adds another civilian
member to a powerful, military-dominated National Security Council.
   Other changes would eliminate the presidential power to send
Chileans into exile and to dissolve the lower house of Congress.
Requirements for future constitutional reform would be eased.
   Both the government and opposition agreed to the text of the
proposed changes.
   Officials said the proposals were viewed as ``democratizing''
the constitution, although the opposition had repeatedly said they
were insufficient.
   ``The constitution continues to be anti-democratic, but it's a
first step which will allow us all to build together a really
democratic institutional system,'' said Ricardo Lagos, a prominent
Socialist leader.
   Constitutional experts and political leaders had said public
apathy during the campaign stemmed from the widespread belief the
proposed changes would be approved even with a small turnout.
   ``There's nothing dramatic about this referendum,'' said Edgardo
Boeninger, vice president of the centrist Christian Democratic
Party, the largest in the opposition.
   ``There is no one to beat this time,'' he told The Associated
Press.
   He also said Chileans had displayed little interest because they
were ill informed and considered the changes very complex.
   Nearly all the major political parties and the government urged
approval of the changes in 40-second television spots broadcast by
all the country's stations. The spots were allocated at no charge
to opposition parties.
   About the only controversy of the campaign broke out when the
government censored at least 10 opposition television spots,
claiming they were illegal. It said they were intended as party
propaganda _ not to clarify the referendum.
   The country's last referendum was Oct. 5, and turnout was 97
percent. At issue was whether Pinochet's rule should be extended
until 1997. The extension was overwhelmingly rejected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
