<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1547EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     07-29 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Kill 12 in Kabul Attacks at Bazaar, Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barrage of rockets fired by Moslem
guerrillas slammed into Kabul on Saturday, with one spraying
shrapnel and glass around a crowded bazaar. At least 14 people were
killed in the attacks, official Radio Kabul said.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said the
U.S.-backed guerrillas are stepping up such attacks to give them
more leverage before Monday's U.S.-Soviet talks on Afghanistan in
Stockholm, Sweden.
   The Soviets, who fought alongside Afghan government troops for
nine years, are the Marxist government's major arms supplier.
   Amani said 12 people were killed Saturday. He said eight people
died and 40 were injured when the rocket hit the bazaar. Other
rockets landed around the center and south of the capital, killing
four people and injuring 16, he said.
   Official Radio Kabul said 14 people were killed and 50 injured
in the attacks. The broadcast was monitored in Islamabad, Pakistan.
   Diplomatic sources speaking on condition of anonymity said they
counted 30 rockets fired Saturday.
   In the past month, the rebels, who call themselves Mujahedeen or
Islamic holy warriors, have been launching long-range rockets from
behind the hills that ring this mile-high capital. More than 200
people have died, virtually all civilians.
   Abdul Halim, a 50-year-old school employee who suffered shrapnel
wounds, said he was walking across the street when the rocket
exploded at the Kote Sangi Bazaar in western Kabul. ``Whoever fired
the rocket, they are anti-Moslem,'' he said.
   ``People are killed from this action, and I want it to stop,''
said a student at the bazaar who identified himself only as
Najibullah.
   At the hospital where many victims were taken, bloody stretchers
sat abandoned in the corridor. A knot of men and women scanned a
list of names of victims.
   Dr. M. Nasser, who refused to give his first name, said three
children were among the dead there.
   Standing in a ward surrounded by moaning survivors, Nasser
denounced both the United States and the Soviets.
   ``The Afghan people don't like the U.S.S.R. and the U.S.A.
because the people think the U.S.S.R. and the U.S.A. want war in
our country,'' he said. ``Afghans want Afghanistan for the
Afghans.''
   Another doctor pointed to his white jacket and said: ``All of us
are wearing coats of peace because we want peace _ no more
revolution.''
   A third doctor, still wearing his operating room mask, added:
``This doesn't mean we don't want good relations with the United
States or the U.S.S.R. because we need their help, but we want our
country back.''
   Other doctors and nurses nodded in approval.
   In the ward, weeping relatives leaned over beds of the injured,
and one man lunged for a doctor, shouting in anger. He was
restrained and led out.
   The guerrillas are fighting to set up an Islamic republic in
Afghanistan. The war began after a 1978 coup that set up a Marxist
government in the country.
</TEXT>
