<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1554EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-DetroitMayor     07-29 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Mayor,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conyers Adds Drama to Detroit Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGELA AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleman Young's campaign for a fifth mayoral term
was considered a breeze until U.S. Rep. John Conyers unexpectedly
entered the race last week.
   The 13-term congressman lacks the local political organization
and estimated $5 million in campaign funds that Young has, but
Conyers is well-known and liked in Detroit. Early polls show him
running tight with Young, and the two dominating the Sept. 12
non-partisan primary in which 13 candidates will be winnowed to two.
   ``It could very well be,'' a close race, Young said late last
week. ``I don't expect any race to be easy.''
   That was a sharp contrast to Young's earlier statement about
Conyers. ``Now that he's in, I will shoot at him like he's a
rabbit.''
   Wilbur Rich, a political science professor at Wayne State
University and author of a biography on Young, played down the
significance of the polls.
   ``If (Conyers) survives the primary, then I think there will be
a very tight and very bitter race. I think Conyers probably thinks
Coleman has something about his personality people don't like and
will try to build on that.''
   Young, 71, defeated Detroit accountant Tom Barrow with 61
percent of the vote in 1985. Before Conyers, 60, entered the race,
Barrow was the favorite to meet Young in November.
   ``Coleman has got one good campaign left in him,'' Rich said.
``I think he will be more colorful, more flamboyant in his campaign
rhetoric. I think he wants to show people he still wants to do the
job.''
   Barrow said he still thinks he will win the right to face Young
again.
   Young, who hasn't faced a real challenge since his first bid for
mayor in 1973, has been under attack this year. Critics accuse him
of failing to reverse the city's chronic crime and unemployment
problems.
   On a more personal level, Young agreed earlier this year to pay
child support following a highly publicized paternity suit in which
blood tests confirmed he fathered the 6-year-old son of a former
city employee.
   Even with a perception of Young's vulnerability, Conyers' entry
into the race baffled some observers who question why he would give
up his seniority in Congress, where he is chairman of the
Government Operations Committee, the House watchdog panel.
   ``I am very puzzled,'' Rich said. ``He's been around a long time
and could really do a lot of good for Detroit in that position,''
in Congress.
   Rich believes Conyers may be laying the groundwork for 1993,
when Young is expected to step down.
   ``I think this is going to be a showcase for '93 ... the
post-Young era,'' he said.
   How long Conyers' popularity will hold out is another question.
   ``I think John has always been a man of symbols, always engaged
in symbolic events,'' Rich said, referring to Conyers' opposition
to the Vietnam War, his involvement in former President Richard
Nixon's impeachment and his support of a holiday honoring the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr.
   ``Whatever his flaws are, they'll come out,'' Barrow said.
   City Council President Erma Henderson also could be a factor in
the primary by siphoning support from Conyers, her longtime friend
with whom she appeared arm-in-arm the day he filed his nominating
petitions. Henderson said Friday she is in the race to stay.
   Most observers think Henderson and Barrow are preparing for
1993, when pop singer Stevie Wonder, an early Motown recording
star, has said he wants to run for mayor.
   Two polls taken last week showed the extent of support for Young
and Conyers. A Detroit Free Press-WXYZ-TV poll showed Young with 31
percent and Conyers with 27 percent of voter support in the
primary. Barrow and Henderson trailed with 13 percent and 9 percent.
   In a Detroit News poll, 44 percent said they would vote for
Conyers in a runoff, while 43 percent would suppport Young.
   Both polls questioned 500 registered voters and were conducted
Tuesday and Wednesday, after Conyers announced Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
