<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-May     07-29 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-May,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Lutheran Bishop Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Kenneth R. May, retired bishop of the
Western Pennsylvania-West Virginia Synod of the former Lutheran
Church in America, has died. He was 65.
   May died Friday in Allegheny General Hospital of complications
of an aortic aneurysm, said Bishop Donald J. McCoid, who heads the
Southwestern Pennsylvania Synod of the Evangelical Lutheran Church
in America.
   May retired as bishop Dec. 31, 1987, when the Lutheran Church in
America merged with the American Lutheran Church and the American
Evangelical Lutheran Church to form the Evangelical Lutheran Church
in America.
   May headed the 151,000-member LCA synod from 1974 to 1987.
   ``He was a person who was a strong and sensitive leader, a very
good friend and a person who loved the church dearly,'' McCoid said.
   May led the synod in the mid-1980s during its conflicts with the
Denominational Ministry Strategy, a confrontational movement that
aimed to call attention to the plight of the unemployed. May
ordered two pastors involved with the movement to give up their
pulpits.
   May was born in New Brighton, northwest of Pittsburgh.
   He is survived by a wife, a son, two daughters, and a grandchild.
</TEXT>
