<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1620EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Chernobyl     07-29 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Chernobyl,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Byelorussians Debate Evacuation from Chernobyl Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists say 106,000 people should be evacuated
from their villages in Byelorussia due to contamination from the
Chernobyl nuclear accident, not 11,000 as the government
recommends, Tass said Saturday.
   Scientists and legislators speaking before the Byelorussian
Republic's legislature also said a broader program is needed to
provide a normal life for people of the region, the official news
agency reported.
   The cost of such a large resettlement would reach $15.6 billion,
well beyond the finanical capabilities of the republic just north
of the power plant, which is in the Ukraine.
   The estimate exceeds the $12.5 billion official figure for the
cumulative cost of the Chernobyl cleanup.
   An explosion at the plant, the worst nuclear accident ever,
scattered radiation across hundreds of miles. The accident killed
31 people, according to official accounts.
   ``Chernobyl is a disaster of the whole country, so the whole
country must participate in curing the wounds,'' Tass said in
describing the arguments presented at the legislative session. It
did not say when the meeting was held.
   The deputies, who were not identified, argued that over eight to
10 years, complete resettlement would be less expensive than trying
to improve living conditions in the contaminated area.
   A Byelorussian parliamentary commission will consider the
question, Tass said.
   More than 130,000 people have been evacuated from homes in the
immediate vicinity of Chernobyl.
</TEXT>
