<FIRST>r i AM-Guatemala-Drugs     07-29 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala-Drugs,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Men Believed to be Americans Arrested on Yacht with Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men believed to be Americans were
arrested on board a yacht loaded with 1,700 pounds of cocaine worth
about $170 million, authorities said Saturday.
   Spokesmen Eduardo Santis of the Treasury Ministry and Guillermo
Moliendo of the National Police told a news conference the yacht
Lydia was seized Friday about eight miles off the port of San Jose
by a law enforcement task force that included army and navy units.
   The spokesmen identified the crewmen only as Gary Elliot Kent
Jr. and Phillip C. Carr and said authorities believed they were
Americans citizens.
   A source at the U.S. Embassy, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the embassy had sent a staff member to San Jose to
help determine their nationalities.
   The men were being held Saturday in San Jose, 67 miles south of
Guatemala City.
   Santis and Moliendo said the Lydia was on a list of boats
suspected of drug smuggling compiled by the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration.
   They said authorities believed the yacht was on its way from
Colombia to Los Angeles with the cargo of drugs.
