<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1721EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Defections     07-29 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Defections,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Romanian Canoeists Defect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DARTMOUTH, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Romanians defected Saturday
at the world junior canoe championships, officials said.
   The two men and a woman apparently asked to remain in Canada,
said Immigration Department spokesman John Stone. Their names were
not released.
   The trio contacted city police in neighboring Halifax shortly
after 1 a.m. Saturday and were interviewed by immigration officials.
   The head of security for the championships, Bud Snow, said the
three were discovered missing late Friday.
   ``To the best of our knowledge they are desiring to stay in
Canada,'' Stone said in an interview. ``However, they are being
interviewed by senior immigration officials to determine their
intentions.''
   Stone said Halifax police contacted immigration authorities when
the Romanians showed up at the city's downtown police station.
   He did not say where the three were taken or whether they were
athletes, coaches or other participants in the world junior canoe
and kayak championships, sponsored by the International Canoe
Federation.
   The races, which conclude Sunday, include paddlers under the age
of 18 from 30 countries.
   Romania is one the world leaders in paddling, a sport dominated
by the East bloc countries. In the last junior world championships
in Yugoslavia, the Romanians placed fourth behind the Soviet Union,
Hungary and West Germany.
   The paddlers' compound at the championships is off limits to the
public. Reporters can enter only if they are escorted by race
officials.
   The event is taking place on Lake Banook, one of two dozen lakes
in this city across the harbor from Halifax.
