<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1804EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Opposition     07-29 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Opposition,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organize First Opposition in Soviet Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first organized opposition in the Soviet
parliament in nearly 70 years was formed Saturday by 368
legislators who gathered to plan their strategy for greater
political and economic reforms.
   Even the official news agency Tass said the historic event could
be described as ``the birth of the Soviet opposition.''
   Tass called the organization ``left-radical.''
   In another development, Latvia joined the two other Baltic
republics, Lithuania and Estonia, in declaring itself ``sovereign''
with the right to veto Soviet laws on its territory, Tass reported.
   Among the members of the opposition group are human rights
activist Andrei Sakharov; maverick Communist Boris Yeltsin; Vitaly
Korotich, editor of the reform magazine Ogonyoky; and economist
Gavriil Popov. It will operate under the title Inter-Regional
Deputies' Group.
   Elena Kotova, who participated in the meeting but is not a
legislator, said, ``Our desired aim is to have the equivalent of a
Western party.''
   The Left Socialist Revolutionaries was the last opposition party
to survive the Bolshevik purges following the 1917 revolution. It
was suppressed in 1922.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has ordered many reforms since
coming to power in 1985 but has strongly opposed allowing an
alternative party to the Communists.
   Leaders of the new organization said enough contributions have
been received to begin publishing a newspaper.
   Mikhail Bocharov, a deputy from suburban Moscow, said the
newspaper The People's Deputy will start with a circulation of
300,000 and sell for about 80 cents a copy.
   That is more than 18 times the cost of the Communist Party
newspaper Pravda but considerably less than a Soviet fashion
magazine.
   Historian Yuri Afanasiev, a deputy from Moscow, said the group
will meet Sunday and hopes to reach agreement on a platform.
   Tass predicted Yeltsin would be elected leader but Afanasiev
indicated the group is leaning toward a governing council with
several deputies.
   The organization is still a small minority in the 2,250-seat
Congress of People's Deputies, the Soviet parliament. Nikolai
Medvedev, a deputy from Lithuania, said most of his colleagues from
the three Baltic republics had left Moscow for the weekend but when
they returned they could add up to 140 members to the group.
   It was not clear how many of the opposition deputies are also
members of the smaller legislative branch of the Congress called
the Supreme Soviet.
   The group could have its most immediate effect on the political
process by proposing laws. The Supreme Soviet gained that power
this spring but so far it has considered only proposals put forth
by the Kremlin leadership.
   Moscow deputy Sergei Stankevich, writing in the first issue of
The People's Deputy, said that fears instilled by years of
political tyranny made people shy away from an open opposition.
   Popov opened Saturday's meeting in the crowded auditorium of the
Soviet Filmmakers' Union with a call to bring reform through legal
changes instead of what he called the government's ``spontaneous
approach'' to crises.
   Tass said the group has a place in the reform process but
reported some legislators ``have expressed the fear that in this
complex time for the country, when unity of action is required,
this `left-radical group' might turn into some kind of opposition.''
   Organizers of the group said it has been tolerated by the
government bureaucracy and was not allowed to meet in the Kremlin.
   Among issues discussed Saturday were proposals that would give
enterprises more independence and allow Soviets living abroad who
were stripped of their citizenship to reclaim it.
   Tass said the Latvian parliament's declaration of sovereignty
means that ``laws of the U.S.S.R. will go into effect on the
territory of Latvia only after their ratification by the highest
organ of government in the republic.''
   When Estonia declared its sovereignty last November, the Kremlin
called the action unconstitutional.
   On Thursday, however, the Supreme Soviet gave preliminary
approval to resolutions that would give Latvia, Estonia and
Lithuania economic independence by Jan. 1.
   Estonia has tried to assert independence on issues of public
concern, such as environmental protection. Lithuania followed
Estonia's example this summer after its Sajudis reform group won a
majority of the republic's seats in the Soviet Union's first
contested elections for parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
