<FIRST>r a AM-Robinson-Republicans 1stLd-Writethru a0575 07-29 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robinson-Republicans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0575,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republican Convert Robinson Welcomed By Faithful Of New Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Capitalizes Democratic in 1st and 7th grafs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Party Switchers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans held a grand old party
Saturday to welcome their latest convert, Rep. Tommy Robinson, who
defected from the Democratic ranks earlier this week.
   ``I know how hard it is to be a Southern conservative Democrat.
My conscience is now clear,'' Robinson told about 150 cheering
Republicans. ``I have now made my decision and it is the right one
for the people of this state.''
   President Bush announced the three-term Arkansas congressman's
party change Friday. Robinson was the third Democrat in three days
to make the switch.
   Also changing parties were retiring District of Columbia Police
Chief Maurice Turner _ widely considered a mayoral prospect for the
capital _ and Louisiana Secretary of State Fox McKeithen.
   ``That party has shut out Southern Democrats and that party has
lost Tommy Robinson,'' he said. ``I can no longer be a member of
that party.''
   Republican leaders raved about their newest congressman.
   Former Lt. Gov. Maurice ``Footsie'' Britt called it the ``first
crack in the dam'' of recruiting from the Democratic ranks.
   ``He really is a phenomenon,'' said party activist Emaline
Holleman of Wynne. ``I think Tommy Robinson will bring us votes,''
she said.
   Robinson, 47, and his wife, Carolyn, were cheered by an audience
that waved small U.S. flags and swayed to a Dixieland band.
   Meanwhile, Arkansas Democratic Party Chairman James ``Skip''
Rutherford said Saturday that he has already received several calls
from people who are interested in running against Robinson.
   ``People are looking more seriously now,'' Rutherford said.
``There is a lot of interest in the Second District seat.''
   Robinson's move leaves the House with 256 Democrats, 176
Republicans, and three vacancies.
   Robinson said he will meet with Republican House leaders on
Monday to discuss new committee assignments. As a Democrat, he had
served on the House Armed Services Committee, but the switch means
he will lose his old seat.
   The Robinsons were joined on a stage decorated with red, white
and blue balloons by U.S. Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., who praised
Robinson's work on a drug interdiction bill they co-sponsored.
Hunter said he admired Robinson for defying the House Democratic
leadership.
</TEXT>
