<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-29 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain in the West</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rain and thunderstorms moved across parts of South Dakota on
Saturday, bringing up to 5 inches to some areas, while rain in the
Missouri River Valley brought relief to the Corn Belt.
   Rain was measured at 5 inches just west of Virgil, S.D., with 4
inches in the Piermont area and 3 inches in the town of Hecla.
Large hail and 3 inches of rain was reported east of Langford, S.D.
   Generous rainfall was also reported over parts of central and
southern Minnesota. One to 4 inches was reported from Browns Valley
into Redwood Falls along the Minnesota River. Nearly 3} inches of
rain fell in Madison, Minn.
   The showers and thunderstorms extended from upper Michigan
through northwest Wisconsin into southwest Iowa and eastern
Nebraska by afternoon.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms were developing from
Missouri through Arkansas into the central Gulf Coast region.
Showers and thunderstorms were also developing along the eastern
slopes of the Colorado Rockies.
   Temperatures were in the 80s or 90s across much of the nation.
Readings were in the 60s and 70s from the upper Mississippi Valley
through the lower Great Lakes and parts of the Ohio Valley into New
England. Temperatures were in the 50s over parts of the upper Great
Lakes.
   Temperatures were also in the 70s through parts of the
intermountain region. Temperatures reached into the 90s to around
100 degrees across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures in Miami reached 93 degrees tying the record high
temperature for the date set in 1986.
   The low in the nation was 36 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57 degrees at Ironwood,
Mich., to 101 degrees at Needles and Palm Springs, Calif.
   The forecast for Sunday called for showers and thunderstorms
scattered from the lower Great Lakes through the lower Ohio and
Tennessee valleys, the middle and lower Mississippi Valley and into
the central and eastern Gulf Coast region with showers most
numerous across parts of Illinois and Indiana. Late afternoon
showers and thunderstorms were expected over parts of western
Montana, north central Arizona and the southern high Plains.
   High temperatures were forecast for the 80s or 90s across much
of the nation Sunday. Highs in the 70s were expected along the
central and northern Pacific Coast and from the Great Lakes into
New England. Highs between 100 and 105 degrees were expected from
central Texas into the middle Rio Grande Valley and up to 110
degrees across the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
