<DOCNO> AP890729-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1842EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Elections     07-29 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Elections,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Wins Landslide Majority, Sheibani Concedes Defeat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani was
elected president by a landslide majority, according to official
returns announced Saturday.
   Government-run Tehran radio reported Rafsanjani won 13,468,355
out of 14,192,802 votes cast Friday in 192 out of 198 regions, or
about 95 percent.
   It also said 97 percent of the voters approved constitutional
amendments boosting the president's executive power.
   Tehran radio said Rafsanjani's only opponent, Parliament deputy
Abass Sheibani from the token opposition party, the Freedom
Movement, won 483,050 votes, or about 3 percent.
   Sheibani conceded defeat in a letter to Rafsanjani read over the
radio and was quoted as saying: ``I congratulate you on your
election, which was achieved with a definite vote.''
   Iran's official media did not say how many of the country's 25
million voters age 16 or older turned out to vote, or when full
results would be reported. About 17 million people voted in last
year's parliamentary elections.
   Iran's main opposition group, the Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's
Warriors, said in a statement released at its headquarters in
Baghdad, Iraq, that turnout was low.
   Rafsanjani, a so-called pragmatist in Iran's religious
hierarchy, will be the Islamic Republic's fourth president. He will
succeed Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who was chosen supreme leader after
the death June 3 of Ayatollah Ruholla Khomeini.
   Rafsanjani is expected to move toward restoring links with the
West and liberalizing Iran's economy to help the country's
reconstruction after the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, which was
suspended by a cease-fire last August.
   The constitutional amendments approved in the election do away
with the post of prime minister and put the president in charge of
the government, answerable only to the 270-seat Majlis, or
parliament.
   The changes are designed to eliminate competing power centers
that have for years paralyzed the government and blocked economic
reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
