<FIRST>r w AM-Executions 1stLd-Writethru a0520 07-29 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Executions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0520,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>1988 Death Count Half That of 1987</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: DELETES separate reference to Hispanics in 11th graf since they
are included in other race group counts</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 5 p.m. EDT, time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven prisoners were executed in six states
last year, less than half the number of inmates put to death the
previous year, the Justice Department said Saturday.
   The executions in 1988 brought to 104 the total number of
inmates put to death since 1976, when the Supreme Court reinstated
capital punishment.
   The department, in a study by its Bureau of Justice Statistics,
said those put to death during 1988 had spent an average of six
years and eight months awaiting execution for their crimes.
   Louisiana and Texas each executed three inmates last year, with
two in Florida and one each in Georgia, Utah and Virginia. Six
white males and five black males were executed last year.
   During 1988, state courts sent 296 defendants to death rows in
state prisons following their conviction and sentencing for murder,
the report said.
   The death sentences of 116 inmates already on death row were
vacated or commuted last year, the study said.
   At year's end, 2,124 prisoners were under death sentences in 34
of the 37 states that authorize capital punishment. There were no
death-row prisoners in the other three states, according to the
study.
   Of the nation's death-row inmates last year, 1,238 _ or 58.3
percent _ were white and 853 _ 40.2 percent _ were black. The study
said 21 were American Indians and 12 were Asian.
   This group included 23 women.
   State prisons in Southern states held 59 percent of the nation's
death-row inmates last year, while 19 percent were in prisons in
Western states. Sixteen percent were on death rows in state prisons
in the Midwest and almost 6 percent were awaiting execution in the
Northeast.
   The study said that 193 of those sentenced to die last year were
white males while 89 were black males, four were male American
Indians and 5 were male Asians. The group included three while
women and two black women.
   Last year, Florida had the most new prisoners on death row _ 42
_ followed by Texas, where 34 defendants were ordered sent to
prison to be executed. California had 32 new prisoners sent to
death row last year, the report said.
</TEXT>
