<FIRST>r a AM-ChristianChurch     07-29 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christian Church,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disciples Unite with United Church of Christ</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Christian Church (iisciples of Christ), with parentheses, is
cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE BEZICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian Church (Disciples of Christ)
Saturday endorsed a working partnership with the United Church of
Christ, despite criticism from some members that the United Church
is too liberal.
   Delegates to the Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) General
Assembly approved a resolution for full communion between the two
churches, including mutual recognition of members and clergy.
   The resolution means the churches will recognize each other's
members as believers in a single common faith, said Paul Crow Jr.,
the president of the council on Christian unity.
   He said they will also work to coordinate the two churches'
social services and community functions.
   About 6,000 delegates attended the first day of business of the
five-day Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) General Assembly,
officials said.
   The United Church of Christ passed a similar resolution at its
national convention in Fort Worth, Texas, a month ago.
   ``This is not a merger. It's not a uniting of the churches'
structure,'' Crow said. ``This is setting up a common
acknowledgement of each other.''
   The move means the two congregations can attend the same worship
services, but Crow says local churches will maintain their own
identities.
   The Disciples of Christ and the United Church of Christ base
their faith on the same Christian doctrine, Crow said. The two
organizations already work together in much of their missionary
endeavors, but they differ in some worship practices and church
policies, he said.
   One of those policies is a United Church of Christ clause that
forbids church boards from considering sexual orientation of its
ministers. That means the church officially allows homosexuals to
become ministers and forbids member churches from discriminating
against them.
   ``In putting our stamp of approval on this, we are putting our
stamp of approval on homosexuality,'' said Bethel Nason of Topeka,
Kan. Her statements against the resolution brought a round of
applause from delegates.
   The resolution does not mention the issue of homosexuality.
   Disciples of Christ delegate Mike Wolfe of Spearman, Texas,
charged the United Church of Christ is ``far to the left, both
political and ecumenically.''
   But Crow said the differences in social beliefs are as common
within the Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) as they are
between the two denominations.
   ``The Christian Church allows for unity in diversity but that
diversity need not divide us,'' he said.
   Disciples President John O. Humbert also unveiled a model for a
proposed $15 million building in downtown Indianapolis that will
house the Church's international offices. He said construction is
expected to be completed by 1992.
   The Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) was formed in 1832 as
part of an early frontier movement to unify Christians. The United
Church of Christ was formed 32 years ago from other Christian
sects. Both organizations allow for varied opinions and stress
freedom of interpretaton.
</TEXT>
