<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Judiciary     07-29 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Judiciary,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Regime Gives Itself Broad Powers Over Judiciary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's new military ruler further
consolidated power Saturday by decreeing broad judicial powers for
himself.
   The order gives Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan el-Bashir power to appoint
the chief justice and senior judges. He can also commute death
sentences and issue reprieves without explanation.
   The decree, which el-Bashir signed as head of the ruling
15-officer junta, named him ``supreme constitutional authority in
the country.''
   Shortly after Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi's civilian
government was overthrown in a bloodless coup on June 30, el-Bashir
made himself prime minister, minister of defense and military
commander-in-chief of this East African nation.
   He dissolved Sudan's 36 political parties and banned all
newspapers and magazines.
   In the past, Sudan's chief justice was elected by other judges.
Senior judges were nominated by the chief justice and appointed by
a five-member State Council.
   El-Bashir has accused officials of the former government and
many political party members of corruption. He has said those
accused of wrongdoing will stand trial. El-Mahdi has been
imprisoned with about 40 former senior political figures.
</TEXT>
