<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 1936EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChineseStudents     07-29 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Students,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Create Union to Push Democratic Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates attending the First Congress of Chinese
Students in the United States on Saturday created a fledgling
national student union aimed at pressuring China for democratic
reforms.
   After lengthy debate and overnight revisions, delegates ratified
a constitution creating the All-America Chinese Student Union.
   ``It's not perfect enough, but it's really a very good start,''
said Ding Jain, chairman of the congress.
   Creation of the union was the main focus of the three-day
congress, which attracted Chinese students from across the country,
a spokesman for the congress said.
   The union will coordinate efforts to bring pressure on China to
adopt pro-democratic reforms, said Pei Minxin, 31, a graduate
student from Harvard University and spokesman for the congress.
   After ratifying the constitution, the congress voted on a
variety of proposed projects for the union to undertake. The
projects include lobbying governments for economic sanctions
against China, organizing boycotts against China and assuming joint
management with the Chinese Journalist Association of the weekly
newspaper Press Freedom Herald. The paper was founded by a group of
journalists in the United States on June 9, 1989.
   Many of the proposals have been tried by individual student
organizations before, Pei said, ``but now, with the establishment
of this union, there is a legitimacy, a broad-based legitimacy to
these efforts ... and conceivably we will attract more support from
Chinese students across America.''
   The union's creation was brought about by the June 3-4 army
attack in Beijing in which hundreds of pro-democracy demonstrators
were killed in Tiananmen Square, Pei said.
   Chinese students in the United States believed there had to be
other ways to change the government in their native country, Pei
said.
   ``Why not choose another less costly message, such as lobbying
for these individual measures?'' Pei said.
   ``Conceivably Chinese students will work through this
organization to voice their pro-democratic ideas and opinions and
also voice their protests against the human rights violations by
the Chinese government,'' he said.
</TEXT>
