<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 2009EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Graham     07-29 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Graham,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Billy Graham Addresses 90,000 People in Soccer Stadium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American evangelist Billy Graham, on
his fourth visit to Hungary, preached to an estimated 90,000 people
Saturday in a Budapest soccer stadium.
   The stadium seats 70,000, so many people stood on the field as
Graham, speaking from a platform, told the crowd, ``God knows
everything'' and ``salvation is through Christ.'' Organizers said
it was the largest crowd ever gathered in the stadium.
   The predominantly young audience frequently cheered Graham. He
spoke in English and the sermon was translated into Hungarian.
   ``I see we have a capacity crowd here. This is an indication of
the spiritual yearning and hunger,'' Graham said.
   He did not make any political comments but when he arrived
Tusday he said Hungary's religious life was ``at a great historical
turning point.''
   ``I believe our present visit is another sign of this new spirit
of openness and change,'' he said.
   The state news agency MTI published a brief report on Graham's
service and said among those attending the event were Matyas
Szueros, the speaker of Parliament, several Hungarian church
leaders and Mark Palmer, the U.S. ambassador to Hungary.
   On Friday, the Communist Party announced major policy changes
regarding religion.
   The party's Central Committee said the party will not require
that members be atheists and will not interfere in church affairs.
   ``The Hungarian Socialist Workers Party is not an atheist party
but a party committed to the cause of social progress,'' Central
Committee member Janos Berecz said after the meeting in Budapest.
   He told a news conference the party will ensure separation of
church and state.
   There are no official statistics on church membership in
Hungary, but 70 percent of Hungarian Christians are believed to be
Roman Catholics.
   In the past, some party members were known to be Catholics but
they rarely professed their beliefs in public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
