<HEAD>Eastern Flight Loses Tail Cone on Landing in Chicago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines DC-9 lost its fiberglass tail
cone while landing at O'Hare International Airport on Saturday but
taxied to the gate without incident, an airline spokeswoman said.
   Flight 236 from Atlanta to Chicago landed at 10:10 a.m.,
carrying 99 passengers and a crew of six, said Eastern spokeswoman
Bobbi Giordano.
   ``It was three-quarters of the way down the runway, decelerating
in reverse thrust and the tail cone fell off,'' she said. ``The
passengers deplaned normally. While it's not a common occurrence,
it does happen in the airline industry.''
   The tail cone is a fiberglass molding that makes the plane
aerodynamic.
   ``It's no big deal,'' said a Federal Aviation Administration
duty officer who declined to give his name. ``It's just like your
bumper falling off your car.''
