<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 2051EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill-Recovery     07-29 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Recovery,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Oil Spill Could Degrade in Five Years, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Exxon Valdez</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tidal action, erosion and oil-eating microbes
could clean most of the oil from Alaska's spill-tainted shores
within five years and the beaches could be normal again in 10
years, researchers said Saturday.
   Speakers at a conference on the nation's largest oil spill said
the natural combination could clean up the spill without human
efforts.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground March 24 and spilled 10.92
million gallons of crude in Prince William Sound. The researchers
based their conclusions on studies of previous oil spills with
similar characteristics, especially the Amoco Cadiz spill off the
coast of France in 1976.
   The researchers' findings contradicted statements by Coast Guard
Vice Adm. Clyde Robbins, the on-site coordinator of cleanup
efforts. Robbins said Friday that the beaches soiled by the spill
``are never going to be clean.''
   ``I would be very surprised to see a significant amount of oil
(in Prince William Sound) in five years,'' said John H.
Vandermeulen, a researcher at the Bedford Institute of Oceanography
at Halifax, Nova Scotia.
   He and Ronald Atlas, a microbiologist at the University of
Louisville, said studies of the Cadiz incident and other major
spills showed that the ecology of the damaged areas appeared to
have returned to normal within about 10 years.
   The researchers used comparisons of fouled areas with similar
but unspoiled environments to determine what constituted ``normal.''
   ``Most environments I have seen have had recovery to some level
of normalcy within five to 10 years,'' Vandermeulen said. ``Even
heavily oiled marshes have recovered in 11 years.''
   The speed of natural cleanup by microbes is slowed by Alaska's
cold temperatures, he said, but the breakdown of crude oil and
weathering of shores by wind and erosion continues.
   Atlas said oil-eating microbes exist in the area of the Alaska
spill, in small numbers. The Environmental Protection Agency, which
has a research station in Valdez, has found that their numbers have
increased since the spill, he said.
   Atlas also said general degradation of the Cadiz spill appeared
to take around 10 years, even if nothing else was done.
   ``That rate is perhaps reasonable here,'' he said.
   Oil degradation can be sped up with the use of fertilizers
containing nitrogen and phosphorus, a proposal that is being
considered.
   Shore organisms that were destroyed by the spill would also come
back fairly quickly, Vandermeusen said.
   ``Even if we wipe out every one, there are larval ones off shore
waiting to settle,'' he said.
   The experts spoke before an estimated 150 researchers attending
a three-day conference on the effects of the oil spill on people,
animals and the environment.
   The conference, which ends Sunday, is sponsored by the National
Institute of Environmental Health Sciences, the National Institute
for Occupational Safety &amp; Health and the Environmental Protection
Agency, among others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
