<FIRST>u i AM-SKorea-Chinese     07-29 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SKorea-Chinese,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Army Officer and Wife Defect to South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese army officer and his wife
defected to South Korea Saturday through the demilitarized zone
separating South Korea and communist North Korea, the Defense
Ministry reported.
   A government intelligence source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, identified the officer as Maj. Zuo Xiukai, 40, a member
of the Chinese delegation to the Korean Military Armistice
Commission. The commission supervises the 1953 truce agreement that
ended the Korean War.
   The source said Zuo and his wife requested that they be allowed
to go to a third country. He said he did not know what country the
couple preferred but speculated it would be either Taiwan or the
United States.
   ``Obviously they do not want to settle down here,'' he said.
   The Seoul newspaper Hankook Ilbo quoted an unidentifed
govenrment source as saying the couple probably defected because of
their disapproval of the violent military crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators last month in Beijing.
   The Defense Ministry reported they crossed the border into South
Korea from the truce village of Panmunjom inside the demilitarized
zone shortly after 11 a.m.
   It said the two were under the protective custody of the
American-led U.N. Command.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Brig. Gen. Yoon Chang-ro said command
officials were questioning the officer and his wife and planned to
transfer them to South Korean authorities.
   The U.N. Command includes representatives of the United States
and 15 other nations that helped South Korea after North Korea
invaded in 1950. The command has headquarters in the border village
of Panmunjom, 35 miles north of Seoul.
   The government intelligence source said Zuo was the
fourth-ranking officer in the 12-member Chinese delegation to the
Armistice Commission, also based in Panmunjom.
   Seoul-based foreign journalists who became acquainted with Zuo
at Panmunjom said he speaks English and had served in the Chinese
embassies in India and Britain before being assigned to Panmunjom
two years ago.
   Assistant Foreign Minister Lee Jung-bin and other government
officials met Saturday to discuss the case.
   The Taiwanese Embassy in Seoul said it was in contact with South
Korean authorities. Some Chinese air force pilots who in past years
defected and landed their jet fighters in South Korea were allowed
to go to Taiwan, which is governed by the anti-communist
Nationalist Chinese.
   China, which sent thousands of troops into Korea to help North
Korea during the Korean War, was a signatory to the 1953 cease-fire
that halted the conflict.
   Saturday's defection was believed to be the first by Chinese
through Panmunjom.
   In 1981 a Czechoslovak enlisted soldier defected to South Korea
through the border village and three years later a Soviet student
crossed the border and sought asylum.
   Both eventually were allowed to go to the United States after
being processed by a U.N. refugee commission in Rome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
