<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-PrisonLuxury     07-29 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Prison Luxury,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Drug Lords, More Furnished Prison Suites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How do you make yourself at home in prison?
Seventeen drug lords and their lieutenants used mahogany furniture,
satin pillows, ornamental plants, porcelain figurines and a private
sauna, the attorney general's office says.
   One even set up a cottage industry in his suite of cells in
Ciudad Juarez, employing other inmates to make clothing for export,
the office said.
   Photographs of Gilberto Ontiveros Lucero's ``bedroom'' in Mexico
City newspapers Saturday showed a double bed with a thick cover and
piles of pillows, elaborate mirrors and a wall-to-wall and
floor-to-ceiling curtain.
   An investigation into prison corruption began with the
disclosure earlier this month that two of Mexico's biggest drug
traffickers were living in opulent quarters in a Mexico City prison.
   While Ontiveros was branching out into haberdashery, other drug
lords continued to run their narcotics businesses, using cellular
telephones to call the United States and Colombia, the attorney
general's office said.
   A total of 14 cellular telephones have been confiscated, the
office said Friday when it released an inventory.
   The inventory listed microwave ovens, video cassette players,
plants, refrigerators, an exercise bicycle, sauna baths, porcelain
figurines, dining room furniture, bedroom furniture, office
furniture and a jewel-encrusted Rolex watch.
   Tear gas, pistols, knives, scanners to monitor police radio
traffic, cocaine and marijuana also were found, the statement said.
   The drug lords, men who go by nicknames like The Beast and The
Quiet One, are now making do with the more Spartan surrounding of
the high-security unit at the Southern Prison in Mexico City.
   They were transferred on July 21 from prisons in Ciudad Juarez,
Nuevo Laredo and Tijuana in a special operation by federal agents.
   The attorney general's office also has begun an investigation
into prison officials. It said the luxury in which the drug barons
were allowed to live showed the degree of their ``economic power
and the internal control based on terror.''
   Earlier this month the director of prisons admitted that Rafael
Caro Quintero, accused of masterminding the 1985 torture-slaying of
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent Enrique Camarena
Salazar, was living with his uncle and fellow drug lord in a space
designed for 250 inmates.
   Walls had been knocked out to enlarge the cells, which were then
outfitted with marble baths, a pool table, air conditioning, guest
quarters and wardrobes crammed with dozens of silk shirts.
</TEXT>
