<FIRST>r a AM-FarmDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0599 07-29 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0599,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Farmers Who Died In Manure Pit Buried</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Sheriff's officials ...' with 2 to CORRECT that
farmers died at different times, sted all in the pit. Picks up 8th graf,
pvs, `There was...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XMRN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MENOMINEE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five farmers who died trying to save one
another in a manure pit were buried Saturday as the family grappled
with running the 100-year-old dairy.
   ``What forced them down into that pit? It certainly wasn't fame
or glory. It was love,'' the Rev. Leroy Ade told more than 200
people who jammed the Christ Evangelical Lutheran Church for
services for Carl Theuerkauf, 65, his sons Carl Jr., 37, Tom, 28
and his grandson Daniel, 15.
   ``It was true love for God, love for Christ, and love for a
fellow man that caused what we termed a tragedy,'' Ade said.
   Carl Theuerkauf would have turned 66 today.
   The funeral for Carl's cousin, Bill Hofer, 63, was held later at
Faith Lutheran Church in nearby Marinette, Wis.
   The five were overcome by methane fumes Wednesday morning trying
to save each other at the Theuerkauf family dairy barn in Menominee
County.
   Sheriff's officials believe Hofer, a farm employee, went into
the 12-foot-deep pit first _ perhaps to clear a drain _ and
collapsed after breathing the fumes, which are produced by manure.
Each one followed to rescue the man before.
   Hofer was dead when deputies arrived, said Menominee County
Sheriff Deputy Gary Corwin. Three others died later Wednesday
morning at Bay Area Medical Center in Marinette, Wis., and the
fifth was pronounced dead at Children's Hospital of Wisconsin at
Wauwatosa, Wis., he said.
   There was about a foot of manure in the pit.
   County extension service director Richard Breyer said the entire
community was shaken by the deaths.
   As a one-mile procession of mourners followed the hearses
through town to a country cemetery, Menominee residents stood by
their front windows and watched. Some stood outside in the rain and
others pulled their cars off the road.
   The Theuerkauf farm has passed from father to son for more than
100 years. Now the only direct adult heir is Carl's third son,
Bill, who was badly injured in an auto accident three years ago.
   Ade said the women will now run the farm.
   Breyer said Carl Sr.'s wife, Dorothy, would meet with him Sunday
to discuss how to handle the dairy farm, among the Upper
Peninsula's largest. The operation likely will have to be cut back.
   A memorial service was planned Sunday morning at the Menominee
County fair, said fair manager Shirley Charlier. The county Farm
Bureau closed down its fair booth this year so that volunteers who
would have worked it could help the Theuerkaufs instead.
</TEXT>
