<FIRST>r a AM-AirplaneMalfunction     07-29 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airplane Malfunction,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Loses Primary Hydraulic System Just Before Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines 727 passenger jet
lost its hydraulic system just before landing Saturday, forcing the
pilot to manually lower the aircraft's landing gear, officials said.
   None of the 34 people aboard Flight 1042 from Raleigh, N.C., was
injured during the 4 p.m. landing at Greater Rochester
International Airport, said a Monroe County sheriff's deputy, who
asked not to be identified.
   ``There was a loss of primary hydraulics,'' said American
spokesman Jim Brown in Dallas, Texas.
   A manual back-up system was used to lower the landing gear,
Brown said. The plane had to be towed down the runway once it
landed.
   The airline had not determined why the hydraulic system
malfunctioned. The jetliner would be grounded while the
investigation continued, Brown said.
   Passengers on the American Airlines jet said they first learned
the jetliner was in difficulty when the pilot made an announcement
minutes before it was supposed to land.
   ``He said we can't get the landing gear down,'' said Bernie
Wight, 52. ``Everyone said, `Oh No!'''
   The jetliner, Wight said, circled Lake Ontario while the landing
gear was put down manually.
   On July 19, a United Airlines DC-10 crashed when a rear engine
blew apart, causing complete hydraulic failure. The plane landed in
a fiery somersault, killing 111 people.
   Elsewhere, two other minor airline incidents were reported on
Saturday.
   In Chicago, an Eastern Airlines DC-9 lost its fiberglass tail
cone while landing at O'Hare International Airport but taxied to
the gate without incident, an airline spokeswoman said.
   Flight 236 from Atlanta to Chicago landed at 10:10 a.m.,
carrying 99 passengers and a crew of six, said Eastern spokeswoman
Bobbi Giordano.
   In Newark, N.J., a United DC-8 with 197 passengers had to shut
down one of its four engines before touching down Saturday night at
Newark International Airport, but landed safely, authorities said.
There were no injuries reported in either incident.
