<UNK>Congressmen Sought Funds for Defense Group From Defense Contractors</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five congressmen on committees that oversee
defense spending helped raise money for a pro-defense group from
contractors who do business with the Pentagon, according to a
published report.
   The Washington Post, in its Sunday editions, reported seven
major defense contractors contributed $100,000 each in tax
deductible donations towards formation of the Institute for the
Common Defense after four of the congressmen, one of them since
deceased, invited them to a dinner in the fall of 1987.
   The congressmen included William Dickinson of Alabama, the
ranking Republican on the House Armed Services Committee, a
longtime friend and former business partner to ICD's president,
Anthony S. Markris, said the Post.
   Joining Dickinson in soliciting funds for the institute were:
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a member of the Armed Services Committee;
Sen. J. Bennett Johnson, D-La., who sits on the Appropriations
defense subcommittee; and the late Rep. Bill Chappell, D-Fla., then
chairman of the subcommittee, the newspaper reported.
   Dickinson and Rep. Marvin Leath, D-Texas, invited the sponsoring
firms to another fundraiser for the institute last May, according
to the Post. But the contractors decided to end their support when
they learned no new contributors had been brought into the venture
since the first appeal in 1987.
   Dickinson and Leath also received speaking fees of $20,000 and
$15,000 respectively from several of the same companies that helped
established the group, the newspaper said.
   The institute's stated goal was to publicize the value of the
defense industry.
   General Dynamics donated to the group because there ``was a
definite feeling there was a need for this type of activity,''
company spokesman Alvin Spivak told the Post.
   ``It didn't hurt that it was supported by Congressman
Dickinson,'' he said. ``It probably helped.''
