<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 2312EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LoanInvestigation     07-29 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Loan Investigation,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Loan to White House Aide Investigated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special prosecutor is investigating whether an
aide to President Bush violated federal ethics laws by failing to
repay a $5,000 loan, a newspaper reported.
   Dan Webb, a former U.S. attorney in Chicago, is trying to
determine whether a 1984 loan to James W. Cicconi was legitimate or
if it represented an illegal gift or bribe from executives of a
troubled Maryland mortgage company, the Chicago Tribune reported in
its Sunday editions.
   Cicconi, 37, runs the White House appointment office.
   The newspaper reported that the ``balloon''-type loan from First
American Mortgage Company was made in September 1984 for an
original term of 90 days. Under the arrangement, Cicconi did not
have to pay interest, which amounted to 10 percent a year, or
principal until the loan expired, and in December 1984, First
American exercised an option clause that extended the loan for an
additional year.
   The mortgage company sought protection under federal bankruptcy
laws in late 1985, and its owner and other executives later were
convicted on federal charges of defrauding company investors of
millions of dollars.
   Cicconi's lawyer, William B. Hundley, said Cicconi tried on
several occasions after the extension expired in December 1985 to
repay the loan and its accumulated interest. But Hundley said
Cicconi ``just couldn't get any information at all as to who owned
the note,'' or where to send the money.
   The Tribune said at least one former executive of the mortgage
company has told investigators that an intermediary asked him to
``do him a favor and make this loan (to Cicconi) and that it was
not to be paid back,'' presumably to win influence at the White
House.
   The intermediary, an executive for a branch of a major Wall
Street investment company, has denied making such a request, the
newspaper's sources said.
   Hundley said Cicconi never talked to the intermediary himself
and was preparing to quit his job in the Reagan White House and
enter private law practice at the time he sought the loan.
   The newspaper said that a federal official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said evidence presented to a federal grand
jury over the last six weeks ``appears to be supporting Cicconi's
view that it is a legitimate loan.''
   The official said the inquiry, which could last several more
weeks, ``may very likely not lead to the indictment of anybody.''
   ``It is my understanding that their probe has cleared (Cicconi)
of any wrongdoing, and that they're going to close it out very
shortly,'' Hundley said.
   Cicconi declined through Hundley to be interviewed.
   Hundley said he now is negotiating repayment terms with a
trustee of the company's assests appointed recently by the
bankruptcy court.
</TEXT>
