<FIRST>r a AM-HUD-Reagan     07-29 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Reagan,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: HUD Insured Project After Ex-Reagan Aide Intervened</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An $11.6 million HUD-guaranteed loan for a
California housing project was approved after a campaign strategist
for Presidents Bush and Reagan intervened, The New York Times
reported in its Sunday editions.
   Lou Kitchin, who was Reagan's southern political director in
1984 and was a senior campaign adviser to Bush last year, told the
Times he was paid about $30,000 for his assistance on the San Diego
project.
   Documents obtained by the newspaper indicate regional officials
of the Department of Housing and Urban Development had opposed the
apartment complex for the elderly for economic reasons.
   But they were overruled in 1987 by political appointees in
Washington, the Times said.
   Deborah Gore Dean, a friend of Kitchin who was then executive
assistant to Housing Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr., was involved
in getting the project approved, the Times said.
   An earlier report said Kitchin received $40,000 in consulting
fees for an $11 million project in Durham, N.C., that converted a
former hosiery mill into HUD-subsidized apartments for the elderly.
   One of that project's largest supporters was Durham Mayor
Charles Markham, who was a former law partner of Pierce.
   Kitchin, an Atlanta-based consultant, has ties to Reagan dating
back to 1976, the Times said.
   Kitchin told the Times that he met repeatedly with Ms. Dean.
   ``You needed her help to understand what was going on at HUD,''
he said.
   The Times said Ms. Dean declined to be interviewed.
   Kitchin said the San Diego project was a good program that
deserved federal support. He said he was retained at the project's
inception.
   The developer of the 145-apartment Woodcrest retirement complex,
Jack K. Jaynes, told the Times that Kitchin's intervention was
essential to the success of the project.
   Jaynes said Kitchin ``told me he would talk with somebody in
Washington, that he was up there frequently, that he knew all of
these people.''
   Jaynes said he remembered talking with Kitchen about Ms. Dean.
   ``It was pretty plain that Deborah Dean was the power in the
secretary's office,'' Jaynes told the Times.
   HUD has been the subject of internal, congressional and Justice
Department investigations. Mismanagement and abuses have been found
in a number of the multibillion-dollar agency's programs.
   Kitchin, however, has attracted almost no attention from
congressional panels investigating possible political influence at
the housing department under Reagan.
</TEXT>
