<FIRST>r a AM-TrainDerailment 2ndLd-Writethru a0616 07-29 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Train Derailment, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0616,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Train Partially Derails, Hundreds Evacuated</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `The evacuation...' to UPDATE with material turning
out to be lard sted battery acid. Picks up 3rd graf, `The derailed...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASSOPOLIS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Grand Trunk Western Railroad train
partially derailed Saturday, forcing several hundred residents from
their homes for about 5{ hours, officials said. No injuries were
reported.
   The evacuation was ordered after what officials believed was
battery acid was found leaking from one of the 24 of 67 cars that
derailed, said Grand Trunk spokesman Tim Weir. The material turned
out to be lard from a car of cow hides, Weir said. The material was
contained and the cargo was loaded on other flatcars so it could be
moved, he said.
   The derailed cars toppled a utility pole, briefly knocking out
electrical and telephone service in this community just north of
the Michigan-Indiana border, said Sgt. Rod Cruzen, of the Cass
County Sheriff's Department.
   The train was headed to Chicago from Detroit. Grand Trunk, a
subsidiary of Canadian National Railways, services industries and
agriculture in Michigan, Illinois, Ohio and Indiana.
   In Freeland, Mich., about 200 people evacuated from their houses
following a fiery train derailment eight days ago were allowed to
go home Saturday night after air quality tests being conducted by
Michigan health officials and CSX Transportation Inc., showed no
evidence of pollution, said railroad spokesman R. Lindsay Leckie.
   Seven loaded and seven unloaded cars derailed July 22 after the
32-car train had nearly completed its run from Port Huron to
Midland. The accident, which is being investigated, sparked a
fierce chemical fire that spewed heavy smoke and burned until
Friday.
</TEXT>
