<DOCNO> AP890729-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 2351EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Mines     07-29 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Mines,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>21 Miners Trapped In Flooded Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CURANILAHUE, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coal mine flooded Saturday night
trapping 21 miners and authorities feared they were dead.
   ``The possibilities of them being alive are almost
non-existent,'' said the town's fire chief, Miguel Cuevas.
   Cuevas said the flood occurred about 7 p.m. when a section of
the mine that was filled with water burst, sending mud and rocks
into a section where miners were working. Four miners managed to
escape and notified rescue workers.
   Cuevas said rescue crews and firefighters were on the scene late
Saturday night, and that it would probably take 12 hours for them
to reach the trapped miners.
   Curanilahue is about 390 miles south of Santiago in the heart of
the Chilean coal mining region.
   The region is wet most of the year and water continuously leaks
into the mines, which contain large pockets of water, Cuevas said.
   He said it had been raining in the area but that there was no
reason to believe that the precipitation caused the accident.
   The mine is privately owned and all work is under contract for
the state coal company, Enacar, Cuevas said. Enacar's rescue crews
were on the scene, he said.
</TEXT>
