<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Violence     07-29 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Violence,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says 110 Maoist Guerrillas Killed in Battles with Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers killed 110 guerrillas of the Shining
Path movement in three battles including one in which 60 rebels and
seven soldiers died, the government reported Saturday.
   It said the fighting occurred Thursday and Friday, during the
Independence Day holidays, in jungle areas northeast of Lima. Peru
celebrated its 168th anniversary of independence from Spain on
Friday.
   A communique carried by the government's Andina news agency gave
this account of the battles:
   Three army units clashed with a group of about 150 rebels
Thursday near Madre Mia, 235 miles northeast of Lima in Huanuco
district. Sixty guerrillas and seven soldiers were killed and 12
troops wounded.
   Thirty rebels were killed in a fight near the town of Nuevo
Progreso, 255 miles northeast of Lima, but the military did not say
if the army suffered any casualties.
   In the third clash near Tulumayo, 220 miles northeast of the
capital and also in Huanuco, 20 rebels and one soldier were killed
and one soldier was wounded.
   The communique said the army captured large caches of arms
following the battles. It did not elaborate.
   The government reported earlier this month that more than 100
Shining Path guerrillas had been killed in Huanuco as army units
and helicopters conducted a series of raids in a counterinsurgency
operation.
   The Maoist Shining Path began its campaign to overthrow the
government in 1980 and the government says more than 15,000 people
have been killed in the fighting.
</TEXT>
