<FIRST>r a AM-Salem-Japan     07-29 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salem-Japan,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salem College Merges with Japanese University</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cash-poor Salem College merged with a
Japanese university and emerged Friday as Salem-Teikyo University
in a deal sweetened with a $12 million endowment by a Japanese
businessman and educator.
   In spring 1990, 100 Japanese students will join the 500 enrolled
at Salem in a program aimed at enriching the lives of the two
groups by helping them learn about each other, said Dr. Shoicki
Okinaga, chairman and president of Teikyo University of Japan.
   Eventually, 500 Japanese students will be integrated with 500
American students, who will share dormitory space and take classes
in both English and Japanese, said Percy Ashcraft, spokesman for
Salem.
   Okinaga told the crowd present for the announcement he gave
Salem the $12 million endowment to help it remain operational as a
school for international education.
   The school, with three major buildings on its northern West
Virginia campus, was in financial trouble when Okinaga and school
officials got together through the assistance of Sen. Jay
Rockefeller, D-W.Va., who spent three years studying in Japan.
   Ronald E. Ohl, president of Salem College and president of the
new university, said Rockefeller was the key to the merger, which
fuses the two schools but retains American control of Salem-Teikyo
and its private status.
   ``This is absolutely an extraordinary occurrence,'' Rockefeller
said. ``We're talking about the beginning of an entirely new
university for West Virginia. I am astounded by it, awed by it,
thrilled by it.''
   ``International understanding and the partnership of Japan and
the United States will be furthered by this unique educational
venure,'' said Okinaga, who also is a physician and educator.
``Salem-Teikyo University will represent the very best
American-international education opportunity.''
   Teikyo University, with campuses throughout Japan, was founded
in 1966.
</TEXT>
