<DOCNO> AP890729-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0827EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Cherry Adv01   07-29 1113</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Cherry, Adv 01,1158</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tue AMs, Aug 1 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Family Affair for Don and Neneh Cherry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don Cherry is going back to his roots; Neneh
Cherry is still developing hers.
   He moves and speaks in the rhythms of cool jazz, spontaneous and
refined; she is warm and down-to-earth, with just a hint of the
passion and hot funk generated by her hit single, ``Buffalo
Stance.''
   His peers include jazz greats Ornette Coleman and Miles Davis;
hers are such pop royalty as Prince and Madonna.
   But listen closely, and a similar spirit can be heard _ what Don
Cherry might refer to as ``world music,'' or what Neneh Cherry
would call ``positive energy.''
   Don is Neneh's stepfather, and they share a common outlook on
life and music. They talked recently about their music and lives in
an interview at Neneh's midtown Manhattan apartment.
   ``It's wonderful what's happening,'' said Don Cherry, the jazz
trumpeter who has just released ``Art Deco,'' his first studio
album of straight jazz in over two decades.
   ``The whole planet has this connection of music and sound.
Russia and Japan and Africa _ everyone's trying to express
themselves. In the past three years, there's been a lot of energy
and acceptance of things fresh.''
   He includes Neneh's ``Raw Like Sushi'' album in that category.
   ``What Neneh's doing in music is what all people can relate to,
the whole planet. There's a lot of things happening now that are a
blessing. I hear Neneh's songs on the radio, that's a blessing. And
all of us feel that way. It's a new generation.''
   The Cherrys trade compliments with ease and joy, celebrating
their music and each other. Don sees Neneh's career as a
continuation of her happy upbringing.
   ``Neneh's always been a person to be with people,'' he said.
``She's always socialized. That's her karma. So many people are
making records where they do everything, the drum parts and all. I
don't think Neneh could be like that, she enjoys working with
people.''
   Neneh was born in 1964 and grew up in Sweden and New York,
leaving school at age 14. After appearing in a number of
underground bands, she began working on ``Raw Like Sushi'' last
year.
   ``Music has always been natural to me,'' she said, ``but I
didn't really make the decision to get involved with it until I was
involved with working in a group.
   ``Music's always been there like a way of life, always. But I
didn't start writing any material until I was out of two band
situations. I took everything I had learned from the rest of my
life and did something with it.''
   ``Buffalo Stance'' combines rock, jazz, funk and disco.
   ``The best blessing I've had in my life is feeling I don't have
to define the various influences. `Now we're going to do a reggae
song, a jazz song.' In `Cat on a Hot Tin Roof,' Paul Newman's
saying, `I need the click in my head, then I'll feel all right.'
   ``At some point, a few years ago, I got that click. It's given
me the freedom to make songs. We're in tune to where the raw energy
is.''
   ``The Next Generation'' is a track off ``Raw Sushi.'' Neneh, a
mother of two, is already thinking of a world far removed from the
dance floors where her music is heard.
   ``When you have a child, all of life and all children begin to
matter in a different way,'' she said. ``It opened me up. Children
are not being given the right information and they need to learn.''
   ``You become aware of education,'' Don added. ``When Neneh was
growing up, we started visiting schools ourselves; that's what
education is. Not in material things, or this false love. The most
important thing you can give kids is yourself.''
   Don Cherry, born in 1936, grew up in the Watts section of Los
Angeles and was soon exposed to Billie Holliday, Charlie Parker and
other jazz legends. Like Neneh, music was more important than
school, and he began cutting classes for the chance to jam with
local musicians.
   He was just 17 when he started playing with Coleman, the alto
sax player who helped develop free jazz, which relied on
spontaneous interaction between musicians rather than extended
solos.
   In the late 1950s, Cherry was part of the Coleman quartet whose
engagement at New York's Five Spot Cafe attracted worldwide
attention.
   He also played with Sonny Rollins and John Coltrane and made his
first visit to the Third World in the mid-'60s, going from
Copenhagen to Morocco, and soon incorporated new sounds into his
music.
   ``You look at the catalogs in the record stores,'' he said,
``the jazz department, new wave, fusion, new age. It's all coming
together, it's world music.
   ``We're growing as listeners and as players, too. We've become
more aware of what we have to work with. Jazz has gotten to be a
gumbo. America's a gumbo. It's good to know about each other's
culture. It's one of the greatest forms of education and it's
happening in all of music.''
   For ``Art Deco,'' he plays with just three other musicians, all
longtime friends: tenor saxophonist James Clay, bassist Charlie
Haden and drummer Billy Higgins.
   They recorded 10 songs, including three Coleman numbers (``The
Blessing,'' ``When Will the Blues Leave'' and ``Compute''), the
standards ``Body and Soul'' and ``I've Grown Accustomed to Your
Face,'' and the title track, a Cherry composition.
   ``It was a pleasure,'' he said. ``We had the best engineer in
jazz (Rudy Van Gelder), the producer (John Snyder) had his heart in
it and the musicians had been playing together. We played at the
Village Vanguard for one week and at the end of the week we started
recording.
   ``It's a pure jazz record.''
   The Cherrys talk excitedly about working together and recording
each other's material. Both see music as a way of communication.
   ``Music is good that way,'' Don said. ``A lot of people don't
handle music because it makes you compoletely nude. You play music
and you can find a whole person's innerself. When you're creating
and improvising, you have to be real honest.''
   Neneh spoke of her song, ``Manchild,'' and how it expressed her
idea of personal growth: ``It's about a man who feels inadequate,
feels he has to establish himself materially in a certain kind of
way.
   ``You see a lot of people, aggressive people who are macho
because they're insecure. ... I'm in touch with myself and I'm
getting to know myself more.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, Aug. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890729-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0837EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv01   07-29 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 01,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release AMs Tuesday, August 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Corporate Dieting All Over Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like that friend of yours who regularly embarks
on slim-and-trim diets, American industry is doing its thing again.
It is seeking to slice poundage from its bureacracy, the better to
court the consumer.
   Some of the biggest companies in America are doing it. Usually a
company is measured large because of its sales and earnings. In
this instance, some of the them are large also because of their
bulging midriffs.
   Faced with competition that seems to grow more intense as
foreigners invade each other's markets, companies are cutting much
of their excess baggage _ plants, products and people.
   Almost all the big-name companies, the kind that seek to sell
worldwide, are doing it. Not all of them are American companies
either.
   The currency advantage that once gave Japanese firms an edge in
exports is greatly reduced now, so they must become even more
efficient. Europe may become a vast common market in 1992, adding
greatly to competitiveness there.
   But it's an old story in the United States. There was little
industrial fat to be found in American companies right after World
War II, but the easy days of the 1960s took care of that. Waste and
inefficiency developed.
   By the 1970s, American companies were finding themselves at a
competitive disadvantage. The industrial might of Europe and Japan,
destroyed in the war, was much newer and more technologically
efficient than American factories.
   The effect was shocking. The products of the bloated
bureaucracies and dated factories of America were undercut by
foreign products shipped thousands of miles to showrooms. Foreign
quality steadily improved while America's fell.
   That shocking experience brought on a crash diet. Old factories
were closed. Layers of white-collar workers were eliminated.
Billions of dollars were spent on new production facilities.
Nonessential units were sold off.
   That desperate diet of the 1970s had much to do with the success
of American business in the 1980s. But success, it seems, has its
dangers, the worst of them complacency. Bureaucratic baggage has
accreted again.
   No company, no matter how great its reputation, is immune:
Oldtimers such as International Business Machines Corp. and the Big
Three automakers, post-war phenoms such as Digital Equipment Corp.
and Polaroid Corp., and upstart Apple Computer Inc.
   After a terrible start, the decade of the 1980s has the
appearance of the 1960s all over. The economy has grown,
unemployment has dropped and inflation and interest rates are under
control again. And the fat has developed.
   Just 10 years after having been rescued from the edge of
bankruptcy, and after having cut expenses to the bone, Chrysler
Corp. is now forced to go on crash diet that, it hopes, will save
$1 billion by the end of 1990.
   The proposed cuts reveal where the fat had grown: Chrysler's
white-collar work force, up about 50 percent in six years, would be
reduced by 2,300 staffers. Cost cuts in materials would be sought.
Production would be streamlined.
   There is nothing new in such goals. In theory, such efficiencies
are part of the unrelenting pursuit of good management. In
practice, especially when times are comfortable, both theory and
practice fall into disuse.
   What awakens both of them is competition, and competiton now is
global rather than regional or national. The route to the
consumer's heart isn't is nationality but price and quality.
   Only the slimmest and trimmest can offer it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for AMs Tuesday, July 01</NOTE>
</DOC>
