<FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 0722EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Time Adv30   07-29 1091</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Time, Adv 30,1134</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday July 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bold Bid Reaches Dramatic Climax, But Story's Not Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The courts turned him down. Wall Street turned
its back on him. So Paramount Chairman Martin Davis scrapped his
$12.2 billion hostile offer for Time, vindicating the media giant's
plan to merge with Warner.
   But the story of Paramount Communications Inc.'s seven-week-long
struggle for Time Inc. did not end last week when Davis dropped his
bid and Time completed its $14 billion tender offer for Warner
Communications Inc.
   The next chapters _ revealing what happens to these three
sprawling entertainment-communications companies _ will unfold
months and years from now.
   Time Chairman J. Richard Munro is both optimistic and cautious
about the future of the company that will be known as Time Warner
Inc.
   ``We've got nothing but healthy businesses,'' he said. ``We've
acquired a company that's on an incredible roll.''
   Nonetheless, Munro's company also has taken on an estimated $13
billion in debt to complete the deal. That will crimp some of Time
Warner's plans.
   ``This is going to make it a little tougher on us,'' Munro said
in a telephone interview. ``We are going to probably not be as
aggressive as we might be without that debt.''
   Time's plans overseas _ which it hoped to expand through the
Warner deal _ could be limited because of the amount of money the
company owes. ``Some of that will take capital we won't have,''
Munro said. ``Some things we would have liked to have done will
take a little longer to get to.''
   After Paramount launched its bid, some observers theorized Davis
did not actually want to acquire Time _ and knew he'd fail _ but
hoped to sabotage Time Warner's competitive advantage.
   Regardless of Davis' motivation, ``he did force Time to acquire
Warner through debt rather than stock,'' said Fred Anschel, an
analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``It does limit Time
Warner's financial flexibility over the next year or two.''
   Paramount's offer forced Time and Warner to transform their
planned stock-swap merger into a $70 a share tender offer by Time
for Warner. The only way Time could pay for Warner's 200 million
shares was to borrow.
   But Munro and Warner Chairman Steven J. Ross, who will co-run
the company, evidently don't expect debt to slow them down too much.
   ``You chew on the debt not by cutting creativity or firing
people, but by growth,'' Munro said.
   First on Time's agenda is to decide the breakdown of cash and
securities it will exchange for the 98 million Warner shares not
purchased in the cash tender offer _ what's known as the ``back
end'' of the merger. The amount of cash involved and how much, if
any, debt securities Time issues will help determine the size of
Time Warner's debt load.
   Time and Warner expect to repay that debt through cash flow, an
accounting term that refers to the money generated by their
business. But while the companies stated in June that no asset
sales were planned as a result of the merger, they sound less
resolute now that they've got a done deal.
   Published reports have said Time and Warner were considering
selling Time's Scott, Foresman book publisher and Warner's cable
television operations.
   Munro said he could not imagine a sale of either business, but
added, ``We really don't know what we're going to do until we get
the back end together and refine the cash flows.''
   ``We would try very hard not to sell assets,'' Munro said.
``We'll know within six months.''
   Some observers doubt whether Ross and Munro, two strong
personalities, will be able to get along sharing the top job.
   ``That will be determined, but we know each other awful well,''
Munro said.
   Both executives negotiated the merger, resolving differences
over two years of talks, and weathered Paramount's assault on their
plans. Munro claimed the pair ``survived that without one harsh
word.''
   Ross has served as a co-chief executive once before. He shared
the top spot at Warner with William Frankel from 1967 until
Frankel's death in 1971.
   ``We're putting together two companies that are so healthy, it
makes it easier,'' Munro said. ``The debt makes it a bit more
difficult, but we really feel that's manageable.''
   Analysts believe the debt will cushion Time Warner from any
hostile bids, at least for a while. But plenty of speculation
remains about what will happen to Paramount, which has an enormous
amount of cash.
   Only a few days after the failed bid for Time, Paramount sold
its financial services business to Ford Motor Co. for $3.35
billion, strengthening its ability to buy other companies.
   ``It's simply a question of who they're going to go after and,
if they don't, who's going to go after them,'' said Anschel, the
Dean Witter analyst.
   Paramount Chairman Davis was undaunted in defeat, although his
aggressive run at Time flopped last week before the highest court
in Delaware, where all three companies are incorporated.
   The three-judge Supreme Court panel upheld a lower court ruling
that affirmed Time's right to pursue its long-sought merger with
Warner and told Paramount it had no business interfering.
   ``We believe in making bold moves when they are in the best
interest of Paramount Communications shareholders,'' Davis stated
after the Supreme Court ruled. ``We have just demonstrated that in
our offer for Time ...''
   Davis said Paramount would continue its expansion plans through
acquisitions, mergers, joint ventures or partnerships. But analysts
have predicted his future targets would be on a smaller scale than
Time.
   The company refused to comment on the possibility that it could
find itself the target of suitor.
   During the seven weeks that Time and Warner fought Paramount,
the stock market was rife with rumors that bidders would emerge for
any or all of the three combatants. Their stock prices gyrated as
the reports came and went, but no bids were announced.
   Still, the failure of Paramount's bid is an interesting study of
how Wall Street itself studies an offer.
   After Paramount announced its bid on June 6, the stock market
bid Time shares up from $126 to a high of $182.75. But professional
speculators and their own lawyers assessed Paramount's chances and
saw that Davis would lose _ and began to dump their Time holdings.
   As the weeks wore on, Time stock spiraled downward, reaching
about $136 as the Supreme Court heard the final arguments in the
case.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday July 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
