<FIRST>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv29-30   07-29 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Week's Business, Adv 29-30,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions July 29-30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bad Week For American Automakers and the UAW</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Autoworker unionists in Tennessee and automaker
executives in Detroit are finding they have a lot in common: Both
know what it's like to get their snouts snapped by Japan.
   The United Auto Workers union suffered a stunning defeat this
past week at the Nissan Motor Corp. plant in Smyrna, Tenn., where
workers voted 2-to-1 to reject UAW representation despite an
intensive and often bitter union campaign that began in January
1988.
   Not only did the rejection signal a repudiation of the UAW's
``Union Yes'' drive at the 6-year-old plant, but it also was seen
as a sign that American workers are increasingly accepting Japanese
management techniques.
   Nissan's Smyrna workers, who produce light trucks and Sentra
sedans, make the same money as UAW counterparts elsewhere and none
has ever been laid off, making it difficult for the union to find
an effective campaign issue. The UAW blamed the defeat on what it
called Nissan's systematic anti-union rhetoric.
   The vote was big news in Japan, where companies that rely
heavily on sales in the U.S. market, particularly automakers, have
been building more factories in the United States, both to thwart
charges of trade protectionism and to gain a stronger presence in
this country.
   So far, no transplanted Japanese auto factory has been organized
by the UAW, and the Smyrna vote intensified speculation that the
country's largest union will face more trouble plugging the holes
in its declining membership.
   The union wasn't the only one smarting from Japan's influence on
the automaking industry.
   Five hundred miles north of Smyrna in Detroit, two of the Big
Three reported lower second-quarter earnings because of declining
domestic sales, and a third announced a $1 billion cost-cutting
effort, partly the result of aggressive Japanese competition.
   General Motors Corp. said earnings fell 3 percent from a year
earlier to $1.45 billion, and Ford Motor Co. said earnings fell 15
percent to $1.4 billion. Industry analysts said the rebates offered
by the carmakers not only failed to lure enough buyers but eroded
whatever earnings were left.
   Chrysler Corp. which is to report earnings Monday, confronted
perhaps a more serious problem of growing costs, evoking memories
of gloomy days several years ago when the company needed federal
loan guarantees to stay alive.
   The No. 3 automaker's chairman Lee Iacocca, widely credited with
resurrecting Chrysler, told top managers the company was too fat
and they needed to cut 2,300 white-collar workers from the payroll
by yearend.
   A slump in the auto business has been expected for a while, and
many industry analysts foresee drastically lower earnings at the
Big Three over the remainder of 1989 and perhaps 1990. The
automakers themselves have indicated they agree with that
assessment.
   In one telling sign this past week, Ford bought Paramount
Communications Inc.'s profitable financial services business for
$3.35 billion cash. The purchase was seen as part of Ford's attempt
to protect itself from dependence on selling cars to make money.
   Elsewhere in business and economic news this past week:
   _Bigger evidently is better in the drug business. Bristol-Myers
Co. and Squibb Corp. agreed to merge in a stock swap valued at
about $11 billion, creating one of the largest pharmaceutical
companies. The agreement came a day after SmithKline Beckman Corp.
and Britain's Beecham PLC completed their previously announced
merger.
   _Time Inc. completed its merger with Warner Communications Inc.
after Delaware's highest court blocked Paramount Communication's
hostile takeover attempt of Time. The court's decision was seen as
a major victory for corporate directors whose long-term plans may
conflict with the wishes of shareholders.
   _More evidence of a slowing economy emerged, boosting stock and
bond prices. The government said its broadest measure of economic
growth showed a 1.7 percent gain this spring, well below
expectations. Economists said the Federal Reserve, which has taken
steps to ease credit, would likely continue to do so in order to
avert a possible recession.
   _Exxon Corp. said the cost of cleaning the Alaskan oil spill
would exceed $1.25 billion and was responsible for a plunge in its
second-quarter earnings. The disclosure coincided with a five-month
low in the price of oil, which had been driven higher by fears of
shortages that followed the March 24 spill.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv weekend editions July 29-30</NOTE>
