<SECOND>BC-Weekly Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Advance For Weekend Editions July 29-30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wall Street Shuns Stocks Likely to be Jarred as Economy Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``This analysis ...'' to UPDATE with Friday records.
Picks up 6th graf ``For all of the week ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a long time circling the runway on
dwindling power, the once high-flying economy finally may be
touching down.
   Stock market investors have braced for a possibly difficult
landing by favoring companies that can turn a profit regardless of
economic conditions and dumping ones apt to be bumped around during
impact.
   The economy probably started on its final approach to the runway
during the second quarter when growth eased considerably to a 1.7
percent annual pace.
   Many analysts regarded the report issued this past week on the
gross national product _ the broadest gauge of economic activity _
as a signal that the economy has sufficient power for the
sought-after ``soft landing,'' a period of slow but sustained
growth with falling inflation and interest rates.
   This analysis helped various stock market measures scale to
record heights during the week. On Friday, the Standard &amp; Poor's
500-stock index climbed to 342.15 and the New York Stock Exchange
composite index advanced to 190.38, both all-time highs.
   For all of the week, the market made some impressive progress.
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished the week at
2,635.24, just 0.19 point below the post-crash high reached
Thursday, up 27.88 points for the week and just about 87 points shy
of its all time high of 2,722.42 set in August 1987.
   The NYSE composite index rose 3.23 to 190.38; the NASDAQ
composite index for the over-the-counter market added 3.53 to
452.82; and, the American Stock Exchange market value index was up
3.23 at 374.51.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 179.62 million shares a day, up
slightly from 175.90 million a day the previous week.
   One force driving the market onward was evidence that the
Federal Reserve was fluffing the credit cushion to make the
economy's landing more comfortable. The central bank took steps
this past week to loosen short-term interest rates.
   Declining interest rates bode well for the stock and bond
markets, says Greg A. Smith of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
Hundreds of billions of dollars now invested in money market funds
in the United States could go elsewhere if rates continue to fall.
   ``Any further drops in short-term interest rates as the Fed
shifts policy for recession prevention could also unleash a fairly
powerful flow of money into longer-term financial assets such as
stocks and bonds,'' he wrote in a weekly market strategy report.
   A look at recent Wall Street trends indicates investors have
been discriminating in their selections. Stocks of companies with
earnings swings during business cycles, such as automakers, have
performed weakly for some time while more recession-proof
companies, such as foodmakers and consumer product companies, have
fared better.
   ``The market is really penalizing those companies that will be
bothered by a recession,'' says John D. Connolly, of Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   But Connolly says he sees two chief reasons why a sluggish
economic growth won't deteriorate into a serious downturn, with
widespread layoffs and significant income shrinkage.
   Most importantly, he says, the central bank has ample leeway to
lower interest rates without stirring up inflation.
   ``There's no reason why the Fed has to stay tight,'' says
Connolly. ``In prior recessions, the Fed felt it couldn't loosen
because it's job on inflation wasn't working.''
   The second safeguard is that consumers already have made major
progress in replenishing their savings depleted during the longest
economic expansion in the post-World War II era, Connolly contends.
   A government report released Friday showed the personal savings
rate _ savings as a percent of disposable income _ rose to 5.9
percent in June, well above the sub-3-percent rates that prevailed
a few years ago.
   ``Part of the function of a recession is to reliquify the
consumer,'' says Connolly. ``The consumer is already partially
reliquified.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End of Adv for Weekend Editions July 29-30</NOTE>
